On Sat, 1/30/21, patient received her Covid-19 Moderna vaccine. On Sun, 1/31/21, she got a covid-19 test to prepare for her surgery on Tues, 2/2/21. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On April 1, 2021, Upon arriving home from the vaccine shot (within two hours of the shot) I changed my clothes and noticed hives across my chest and down the front of my stomach. I immediately took a benadryl and they were gone the next morning. On April 24, I again had hives this time up my back and throughout my left arm. I didn't take a benadryl right away and then my lips started to itch/burn and get swollen. I took a benadryl and again the symptoms were gone in the morning. That was Saturday 4/24/21 it is now Monday 4/26/21, and I have not been feeling too well.    Prior to the vaccine, I have never had hives on my body.  Since getting the shot on April 1, 2021, I have broken out twice. Once immediately after, and again 3 weeks later.
LAB_DATA: I have spoken to four different doctors. Three did not recommend that I get the second shot.  I spoke to a HCP  �\_(?)_/�  from a Covid Medical Hotline, and he suggested having an allergy test done to determine whether I am allergic to Polyethelene Glycol, and if so then I would have my answer (do not get the second shot).   I went to an allergist today, and after telling me on the phone that they had the test available, he refused to administer it claiming results are unreliable and that this is still speculation that polyethelene glycol is the cause of anaphalaxyis. Took my money and got me nowhere.   I read a peer reviewed / scholarly / credible research paper that stated that too many antibodies can have a reverse effect. What if I have  antibodies/t cells already from having had Covid, and now the added antibodies from the vaccine are pushing me over that threshold where I'm experiencing adverse effects.  Also important to note -- I am not your average person, I am very petite. In general, I need to take half of the dose that is recommended. See examples my RX doses are lower than normal bc of my body's response. Even for things like advil/tylenol, I take half of the recommended dose. My body is VERY susceptible to medications.  With that in mind, perhaps, one dose of the vaccine  is enough for me.  CDC states that some people have 80% immunity after the first shot, and I read that J&J is only 86% so like.... i think between me having had Covid + 1 shot, I should get the right of passage.

CBC within normal, PT 18.8 APTT 39 D-dimer 1111, CMP showed bicarb 32 creatinine 1.39 E GFR 45 and lipase 146. Initial troponin is 53 with indeterminate to our delta, will follow-up on 6 hour delta. ProBNP 1663 with no baseline available. Patient tested negative for COVID-19. VBG showed pH 7.33 and pCO2 of 61 no baseline pCO2 available. Chest x-ray as per report no acute abnormality, personal impression increase interstitial reticular opacities suspicion of fluid overload/pulmonary edema. CT PE as per report filling defect left descending pulmonary artery consistent with acute pulmonary embolus. Patient admitted to the ICU for further monitoring and evaluation.     Patient started on heparin drip, rivaroxaban factor Xa antibody sent, as per patient he was compliant with Xarelto. Vascular medicine consult done recommended to bridge with warfarin versus start Lovenox. Discussed with the patient, patient prefers warfarin. Patient was started on warfarin INR 2-3. Resumed CPAP for OSA. Venous Doppler lower extremities negative for acute DVT. TTE showed Normal left ventricular chamber size. Estimated LV ejection fraction range 55-60%. No regional wall motion abnormalities. Mildly enlarged right ventricular chamber size and mildly reduced RV systolic function. Estimated RV systolic pressure 46 mm Hg. Moderately enlarged inferior vena cava size with reduced inspiratory collapse (<50%). No hemodynamically significant valvular heart disease. Patient was started on Lasix IV; converted to oral upon discharge. Patient discharged on Lovenox and warfarin. Patient medical condition improved with medical treatment

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 4/4/21 while hiking my heart started beating really fast, which is unusual, but chalked it up to the hiking. Then for several days after that, my heart would randomly ?flutter? but it only lasted a couple seconds, I assumed it was anxiety. 4/11/21 I was on a walk and my heart started beating really fast and it was hard to breathe. I went back home. 4/12/21 I was at work when suddenly my chest felt tight and  it was hard to breathe for a few seconds. Then following that for days it was the fluttering again, off and on, maybe once every other day, but now my chest had started hurting and feeling tight without the heart palpitations. Just all of a sudden a tight chest, this continues every day including today . 4/26/21 I was at work sitting at my desk when my heart started beating wildly, I?ve never experienced anything like that before. It lasted longer than the others and was stronger, and towards the end it was hard to breathe. I spoke to my doctor and she ordered bloodwork. I went to urgent care and they listened to my heart and lungs, and did an EKG and said everything looks good at the moment. I can still feel the chest tightness. I bought a heart monitor so I can track these flutters.
LAB_DATA: 4/26/21: spoke to my doctor, she ordered bloodwork. I went to urgent care and they did an EKG and listened to my heart and lungs, they said everything looked good. They also drew blood to look at my thyroid, I?m waiting on the results.  4/27/21 (tomorrow): I?ll get the bloodwork my doctor ordered done at the lab.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient had standard side effects (fever, fatigue, muscle soreness) day 1 and 2 after vaccination. Starting approx. 3 days after vaccination, patient started noticing altered smell and taste, which has gotten worse in the 14 days since vaccination. Patient also has fatigue and has been experiencing weakness since vaccination. These symptoms are identical to the symptoms the patient had with COVID (starting ~3 weeks after contracting COVID and lasting over a month). The patient contracted COVID in December 2020 and had fully recovered prior to vaccination. Recrudescence of symptoms appears to be due to immunological response to the vaccine.

3 days after receiving the first shot I started to have pain in the hip joints on both sides. At first I thought it was just sore muscles from golfing but it is still present over a month later. Then on April 14 I woke up and both of my ankles felt extremely sore despite the fact that I haven't been doing any physical activity due to the hip pain. By April 15 at the end of the day my ankles were both extremely swollen and I was having a hard time getting around. I finally went in on Monday April 19 to Urgent Care as my PCP couldn't get me in so soon. The doctor there thought it might be cellulitis and prescribed me antibiotics. After taking those for over a week now there has been no improvement. I finally got into my PCP today April 26 and he is scheduling a entire series of lab work to be done. He thinks I have somehow developed vasculitis. He stated that he did not know if that could happen from the vaccine but I had no problems whatsoever and was very active until 3 days after the vaccine shot, so I find it hard to believe that the two things aren't related somehow.
LAB_DATA: Labs are scheduled for April 27 so it will be a few days before I know more.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: After initial dose of vaccine, eczema patch begun spreading up my arms (had only previously had it on my hands).  Some mild lymph node swelling and general fatigue between the first and second vaccine dose. After the second dose I had severe lymph node swelling (up to a baseball size lump under my arm). Within a week of the second dose, I was treated for a sinus infection (though had no symptoms such as congestion) with antibiotics and steroids. After going off steroids, the eczema rash that had occurred after the first shot cropped up again and spread from my scalp to my knees and was extremely itchy. I also had painful, swollen lymph nodes from my ears to collar bone. I was not wheezy, but was coughing and had a tight feeling in my chest frequently. I had to do 2 rounds of steroids, increase antihistamine doseage, and begin a steroid cream (topical). I also had to decrease my immunotherapy doseage significantly because I had more severe responses to my injections. My skin finally cleared after about 4 months though I am still having to take increased medication dosages and decreased immunotherapy doseages.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approx 24 hrs after my first COVID19 Moderna shot I became overcome with severe dizziness that caused me to vomit without pause. During this time I was so dizzy that I could not walk and could barley move. I was completely disoriented. After approx 90 minutes my husband took me to the ER. There I continued to vomit uncontrollably for hours. In the ER they administered an IV, cat scan, and MRI. Scan and MRI were both normal, everything good. I was admitted to the hospital. Hours later I was diagnosed with BPPV. My BPPV is in the right ear in the posterior canal. During my time in the hospital I received 3 vestibular therapy sessions. After leaving the hospital, I received a fourth vestibular therapy at a PT practice. Hospital doctors have prescribed me Meclizine, methylprednisolone, famotidine, promethazine, and vestibular therapy. I still have serious vertigo and cannot drive and do normal activities. I have no history whatsoever of vertigo or dizziness.
LAB_DATA: Vestibular therapy indicated I have BPPV in right posterior canal

On 19-APR-2021, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of Measles, Mumps, and Rubella (Wistar RA 27-3) Virus Vaccine, Live (rHA) (M-M-R II) which went through a temperature excursion of 12.5 degrees Celsius (C) for a timeframe of 24 minutes (product storage error), lot number S029455, expiration date 19-SEP-2021 (anatomical site of vaccination, route, dose, strength, scheme of vaccination, formulation were not reported), as prophylaxis. There was no previous temperature excursion, and a data logger did detect the temperature excursion.   No additional adverse event (AE), the reporter stated that the patient was (no adverse event).

Rheumatoid arthritis/Both jaws replaced due to RA; Blood pressure and oxygen levels kept dropping; Blood pressure and oxygen levels kept dropping; Sleep apnea; Low potassium; Immune disorder; Arm hurt; Very tired and fatigued; Headache; Sick with a bronchial issue; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer based on information received by Pfizer from Amgen (manufacturer control number: US-AMGEN-USASP2021058759), license party for etanercept (ENBREL).  This serious spontaneous report (USASP2021058759) was reported to the company on 15/APR/2021 by a consumer and involves a 48 years old female patient who experienced rheumatoid arthritis/both jaws replaced due to RA [PT: rheumatoid arthritis], blood pressure and oxygen levels kept dropping [PT: oxygen saturation decreased, PT: blood pressure decreased], sleep apnea [PT: sleep apnoea syndrome], low potassium [PT: blood potassium decreased], immune disorder [PT: immune system disorder], sick with a bronchial issue [PT: bronchial disorder], arm hurt [PT: pain in extremity], very tired and fatigued [PT: fatigue], felt a little achy [PT: pain], headache/ bad headache [PT: headache] while receiving Enbrel, Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector. No historical medical condition was reported. The patient's current medical condition included ankylosing spondylitis and rheumatoid arthritis. No concomitant medications were provided. The patient's co-suspect medication included Covid-19 Vaccine. The patient began Enbrel with Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector on an unknown date (lot number: 1123166, expiration date: 31Aug2023). On an unknown date, the patient stated that she was disabled due to her rheumatoid arthritis (RA) and she had to have both jaws replaced due to rheumatoid arthritis (RA). The patient stated that her jaw was blocking her airway when she slept and she had sleep apnea. On an unknown date in MAY/2018, the patient had surgery which lasted for eight hours and 45 minutes. On an unknown date in early 2020, while she was recovering from the surgery, out of nowhere the patient got sick with a bronchial issue. The patient was placed on oxygen and had several pulmonary function tests and CT's done and during this timeframe she was taking Enbrel intermittently. The patient also mentioned that during this time, she was going for physical therapy but her blood pressure and oxygen levels kept dropping causing her to repeatedly have to go to the emergency room for treatment. On an unknown date, on one of her visits she had low potassium and had to have an infusion and her physical therapy was discontinued. The patient was never admitted as an inpatient. The patient also had a bronchoscopy during this timeframe. The patient had immune disorder. The patient stated that once she took her Enbrel for two months consistently and that was unbelievable the difference in how she feels stating, it works very well for her. The patient stated that she was instructed by one of her physician that she could get the COVID vaccine near the end of her Enbrel cycle. The patient stated that she delayed her first vaccine and fell behind on her Enbrel. On an unknown date, with the first COVID vaccine she stated she was very tired and fatigued, her arm hurt, and she had a headache. The patient stated the second day after the vaccine, she felt even worse. The patient Enbrel was due days ago. The patient was informed by one of her physicians that the COVID vaccine would not be as effective due to her immune disorder. The patient asked if there was any information pertaining to when she should take her next Enbrel dose following her vaccination. The outcome of the events rheumatoid arthritis, oxygen saturation decreased, blood pressure decreased, sleep apnoea syndrome, blood potassium decreased, immune system disorder, bronchial disorder, pain in extremity, fatigue, pain, headache were reported as unknown. Action taken with Enbrel and Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was reported as unknown for the events pain, sleep apnoea syndrome, blood potassium decreased, blood pressure decreased, bronchial disorder, oxygen saturation decreased, immune system disorder and rheumatoid arthritis. The causal relationship between the events fatigue, pain in extremity, pain, headache, sleep apnoea syndrome, blood potassium decreased, blood pressure decreased, bronchial disorder, oxygen saturation decreased, immune system disorder, rheumatoid arthritis and Enbrel, Single Dose Prefilled Autoinjector was not provided by the consumer. Follow up has been requested.  Amgen Comment: This safety report does not necessarily reflect a conclusion by Amgen that etanercept, device caused or contributed to the adverse events reported; however, consistent with regulatory reporting requirements, this case is being reported because it contains one or more suspected adverse reactions. This individual case report does not change the safety profile of the product.  Pfizer is a marketing authorization holder of Covid-19 Vaccine in the country of incidence or the country where the product was purchased (if different). This may be a duplicate report if another marketing authorization holder of Covid-19 Vaccine has submitted the same report to the regulatory authorities.; Sender's Comments: Based on the current available information and the plausible drug-event temporal association, a possible contributory role of the suspect products to the reported events cannot be totally excluded. This case will be reassessed once additional information is available.  The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

Smallpox vaccination-associated myopericarditis / Probable Myocarditis; Mild PR depression in lead I; C-reactive protein elevated; Non-deployable; Information received from the review of scientific literature on 02JUL2018.  This is case 3 of 6 (18000138LT, 18000139LT,18000140LT, 18000141LT,18000142LT, 18000143LT)  The article notes a 25-year-old active duty male who presented to the ED with one day of achy chest pain 11 days after receiving ACAM2000. His chest pain was gradual in onset, centrally located, non-exertional, non-positional and without any radiation. The patient had no significant family history of cardiac disease. The ECG showed, ST depression in lead aVL and mild PR depression/ST elevations in lead I. These were new findings compared to a previous ECG. His troponin-I was elevated at 2.24, and his C-reactive protein was elevated at 1.49. No acute cardiopulmonary disease was seen in chest x-ray, and a bedside transthoracic echocardiogram showed no pericardial effusion. Cardiology was consulted from an outside hospital and the patient was transferred for further treatment of myocarditis. After discharge, the patient was placed on ibuprofen and instructed to follow-up with his primary care physician. At follow-up, he was placed on a 3-month medical profile and made non-deployable. He was to be followed by cardiology as an outpatient. The patient's outcome was not reported in the article.   Follow up information was obtained on 04APR2021 during a review of scientific literature:  This is case 4 of 5 reported cases within the article: (cross reference: 21000041LT, 18000141LT, 18000142LT, and 18000143LT).   The additional information received on 04APR2021 included: additional laboratory values, diagnosis and outcome information.  The patient was reported to be a 25-year-old healthy male who received a primary dose of ACAM2000 in April 2018 and was subsequently diagnosed with probable myopericarditis. Symptoms reported included: shortness of breath, diaphoresis, dizziness, chills and fever. Additional significant laboratory findings included HSV 1 (Glycoprotein G Ab IgG): Positive, Epstein Barr Virus Capsid Ab IgG: Positive; Epstein-Barr Virus Nuclear Ab IgG: Positive. For other tests with negative results please refer to relevant Lab section. The patient received follow-up care with a cardiologist for 6 months and serial cardiac imaging. He was placed on limited duty with no exercise for 6 weeks and a non-deployable status for at least 6 months. He was followed by a cardiologist until complete recovery at between 3 and 9 months.  The authors concluded that there was no significant difference observed between the rate seen and the published rates that occurred during the clinical trials. The available evidence suggested that the 5 cases were not an unexpected elevation in the rate of the disease or condition, but rather a predictable number of myopericarditis cases proportional to the increased number of vaccinations performed during a short period of time.  Company comment: This report originated from a literature article describing myopericarditis following smallpox vaccination.  The report of myopericarditis is considered a medically significant event.  The reported events and time interval between immunization and onset are consistent with well described myocarditis/pericarditis known to follow ACAM2000, smallpox (vaccinia) immunization, therefore the causal relationship to ACAM2000 is considered related. Information received on 04APR2021 does not change the previous assessment, Symptoms associated with myocarditis are not entered as adverse event as per MedDRA points to consider.; Sender's Comments: Company comment: This report originated from a literature article describing myopericarditis following smallpox vaccination. Myopericarditis / Probable Myopericarditis; Left-sided pleuritic chest pain; PR depressions; Trace effusion; Information received from the review of scientific literature on 02JUL2018.  This is case 5 of 6 (18000138LT, 18000139LT,18000140LT, 18000141LT,18000142LT, 18000143LT)   The article notes a 27-year-old male who presented to the ED with left-sided pleuritic chest pain 11 days after receiving ACAM2000. His pain was worse with movement, but otherwise non-exertional or positional. His ECG showed diffuse ST elevations and PR depressions. The patient's chest x-ray and bedside transthoracic echocardiogram were unremarkable and his troponin-I was elevated at 0.25. Cardiology was consulted from an outside hospital, and the patient was then transferred for further evaluation and treatment of myopericarditis. The patient was given toradol and started on colchicine prior to transfer. As an inpatient, his formal echocardiogram showed trace effusion, but otherwise, there were no structural changes and he had a normal ejection fraction. Ibuprofen and colchicine were continued and he was followed by Cardiology as an outpatient. The patient was then placed on a 6-month medical profile. Approximately 1 month after initial presentation to the ED, the patient returned with 1 day of similar chest pain. He had been compliant with medication and his initial ECG was normal without signs of ST elevation of PR depression. On repeat ECG, he showed non-specific ST changes in leads II, III, and aVL. His troponin-I was within normal limits and a bedside transthoracic echocardiogram was normal as well. Due to dynamic changes in ECG and recent history of myopericarditis, the patient was transferred to an outside hospital for further evaluation. The patient's outcome was not reported in the article.  Follow up information was obtained on 04APR2021 during a review of scientific literature:  This is case 1 of 5 reported cases within the article: (cross reference: 21000041LT, 18000140LT, 18000141LT, and 18000143LT).    The additional information received included: additional laboratory values, diagnosis and outcome information.   The patient was reported to be a 27 year old healthy male who received a primary dose of ACAM2000 in April 2018; and was subsequently diagnosed with probable myopericarditis.  Additional symptoms reported included: shortness of breath, diaphoresis, dizziness, chills and fever.  His ECG showed diffuse T wave abnormalities with no pericardial effusion. His significant laboratory findings included  HSV 1 (Glycoprotein G Ab IgG): Positive, Epstein Barr Virus Capsid Ab IgG: Positive; Epstein-Barr Virus Nuclear Ab IgG: Positive, Adenovirus Aba: Positive, Parvo B19 (IgG/IgM): IgG+/ IgM+, Coxsackie A7, A9, A16, A24 (IgG/IgM): IgG+/IgM+. For other tests with negative results please refer to relevant test section.  The patient received follow-up care with a cardiologist for 6 months and serial cardiac imaging. He was placed on limited duty with no exercise for 6 weeks and a non-deployable status for at least 6 months. He was followed by a cardiologist until complete recovery at between 3 and 9 months.   The authors concluded that there was no significant difference observed between the rate seen at Facility and the published rates that occurred during the clinical trials. The available evidence suggested that the 5 cases were not an unexpected elevation in the rate of the disease or condition, but rather a predictable number of myopericarditis cases proportional to the increased number of vaccinations performed at Facility during a short period of time.  Company comment: This report originated from a literature article describing myopericarditis following smallpox vaccination.  The event of myopericarditis is considered a medically significant event. The ACAM2000 product information states under the warning section: Myocarditis and pericarditis � cases observed at a rate of 5.7 per 1000 primary vaccines (95% CI: 1.9-13.3). These events are labeled and considered related to the ACAM2000 vaccine. The information received on 04APR2021 does not change the previous assessment. Myopericarditis; Centrally located pleuritic chest pain; Activity restrictions/non-deployable; Information received from the review of scientific literature on 02-JUL-2018. This is case 6 of 6 (18000138LT, 18000139LT,18000140LT, 18000141LT,18000142LT, 18000143LT). Reference.  The article notes an otherwise previously healthy 19-year-old active duty male who presented to the ED with centrally located pleuritic chest pain approximately 10 days after receiving ACAM2000. His pain started the previous night and had been constant and sharp. The patient's ECG was normal without any PR depressions or ST elevations. His troponin-I was positive at 0.83. A transthoracic bedside echocardiogram showed no pericardial effusion and a normal gross ejection fraction. Cardiology from an outside hospital was consulted and the patient was transferred for further evaluation and treatment of myocarditis. An echocardiogram as an inpatient showed systolic dysfunction without signs of heart failure. The patient was discharged 4 days later with instructions to take colchicine and metoprolol. He was being followed by cardiology as an outpatient, was started on ibuprofen, and was placed on activity restrictions for 30 days pending cardiology follow-up, and made non-deployable. The patient's outcome was not reported in the article.  Additional information has been requested.  Follow up information was obtained on 04APR2021 during a review of scientific literature: 2021, (MAR15) [cited 2021 Apr 04] 1-7.    This is case 3 of 5 reported cases within the article: (cross reference: 21000041LT, 18000140LT, 18000141LT, and 18000142LT).    The additional information included: additional laboratory values, diagnosis and outcome information.   The patient was reported to be a healthy 19 year old male who received a primary dose of ACAM2000 in April 2018; and was subsequently diagnosed with probable Myopericarditis.  Additional symptoms reported included: shortness of breath, diaphoresis, dizziness, chills and fever.  His significant laboratory findings included HSV 1 (Glycoprotein G Ab IgG): Positive; prior Epstein interpretation positive for past infection; Epstein Barr virus Ab Igg positive and an echocardiogram showed systolic dysfunction without heart failure. The patient received follow-up care with a cardiologist for 6 months and serial cardiac imaging. He was placed on limited duty with no exercise for 6 weeks and a non-deployable status for at least 6 months. He was followed by a cardiologist until complete recovery at between 3 and 9 months.   The authors concluded that there was no significant difference observed between the rate seen and the published rates that occurred during the clinical trials. The available evidence suggested that the 5 cases were not an unexpected elevation in the rate of the disease or condition, but rather a predictable number of myopericarditis cases proportional to the increased number of vaccinations performed during a short period of time.  Company comment: This report originated from a literature article describing myopericarditis following smallpox vaccination.  The event of myopericarditis is considered a medically significant event. The ACAM2000 product information states under the warning section: Myocarditis and pericarditis � cases observed at a rate of 5.7 per 1000 primary vaccines (95% CI: 1.9-13.3). These events are labeled and considered related to the ACAM2000 vaccine. Information received on 04APR201 does not change the previous assessment. Because pericarditis was ruled out, tmyocarditis was the final diagnosis. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH) in a female patient aged between 12-13 months old, who was vaccinated with unspecified hepatitis A vaccine and unspecified Haemophilus influenzae type B vaccine (manufacturer unknown for all) for prophylaxis.  The patient was born to distantly related but healthy parents at 38 weeks of gestation. Her own medical history was remarkable for significant viral illness: at 9 months of age, the patient had a prolonged febrile illness with seizures, triggered by seasonal coronavirus HKU1 (non-COVID-19) infection. At 10 months of age, the patient experienced severe influenza A (H3) pneumonia with very high fever and progressive respiratory failure despite treatment with oseltamivir, ceftriaxone, methylprednisolone and oxygen delivered by high-flow nasal cannulae. The patient required intubation and mechanical ventilation for 3 days but recovered. Whole exome sequencing of DNA extracted from whole blood of the proband was performed commercially on the Illumina platform by Invitae Corporation. Carriage of the STAT2 variant by the proband, and all family members, was tested by Sanger sequencing of DNA isolated from whole blood by local diagnostic genetic laboratories according to standard methodologies. Suspecting a genetic aetiology in this case, whole exome sequence analysis and addition/deletion testing of 207 genes associated with primary immunodeficiency was undertaken on whole blood DNA from the proband, identifying a homozygous predicted pathogenic variant in STAT2 (c.1999C less than T [p.Arg667Ter]) and a heterozygous variant in DOCK2 [c.54-1Gless than T], the latter of unlikely clinical relevance. Sanger sequencing analysis confirmed the presence of STAT2 c.1999C less than T in the homozygous state in the proband. This variant was heterozygous in both parents and a clinically unaffected sibling, consistent with segregation of an autosomal recessive trait. No information on patient's medical history, family history, concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, 6 days before onset of illness, the patient received unspecified measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine, unspecified hepatitis A vaccine, unspecified Haemophilus influenzae type B vaccine, varivax (varicella zoster virus) vaccine and 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (administration route and site unspecified, dosage unknown; batch number not provided for all). The age of vaccination was not provided but it could be 12 months or 13 months. [Six days before onset of this illness, she had been inoculated with age-appropriate vaccines (MMR, varicella zoster virus, hepatitis A, Haemophilus influenzae type B, and the 13-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccines) despite nasal congestion and clear rhinorrhea]. On an unspecified date, 6 days after the vaccination, the patient presented with high fever, diarrhea, new onset vomiting, nasal congestion, cough, irritability, and lethargy. On admission, her physical examination only showed nasal congestion. The laboratory parameters were largely unremarkable. On day 15 (d15), the patient's laboratory parameter showed: hemoglobin was 8.9 g/dL, hematocrit was 27.3 %, white blood cell count was 9.1x10e9/L, absolute neutrophil count was 3.1x10e9/L, absolute lymphocyte count was 4.6x10e9/L, absolute monocyte count was 0.7, platelet count was 534x10e9/L AST was 73 U/L and ALT was 55 U/L A partial septic screen yielded more than 100,000 colony forming units/ml of Escherichia coli from urine and a positive PCR for rhinovirus/enterovirus RNA from a nasopharyngeal swab sample. Blood cultures collected on days 4 and 6 and were sterile. High fever continued despite intravenous ceftriaxone for presumed pyelonephritis. The patient was on the Paediatric ward for 2 days with continuing high fever up to 41 degree Celsius. On day 3, the patient was transferred to the Paediatric Intensive Care Unit (PICU) because of poor bilateral lower extremity perfusion that failed to improve on multiple fluid boluses. This was accompanied by persistent tachycardia, increased work of breathing, and a diffuse erythematous rash. Extensive imaging revealed no evidence of an infective focus in the renal tract (ultrasonography), chest (repeated plain x-radiography), abdomen/pelvis (contrast CT) or heart (echocardiography). Virology investigations were consistent with human herpes virus type 6 (HHV6) reactivation, based on positive blood PCR (23,500 (log 4.4) copies/ml of HHV-6 type B), positive HHV6 IgG at 1:80 (negative if less than 1:10) and negative IgM (less than 1:20) on day 6. Testing was not undertaken for MMR viruses; samples were not stored to enable retrospective testing. Persistent high fever was accompanied by worsening cytopenias, elevated triglycerides, elevated ferritin to more than or equal to 500 ng/ml, and elevated soluble interleukin-2 receptor level. These results met 5 of 8 criteria for the diagnosis of hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH). An attempt at bone marrow aspiration on day 9 of admission was aborted due to apnea and profound desaturation. The patient was quickly resuscitated and returned to baseline within a few hours while hematologic parameters began spontaneously improving by day 10. Fever abated after 15 days and the patient was discharged on no antibiotics. Treatment with corticosteroids and/or other immunomodulators was planned after the bone marrow aspiration, but not administered because of clinical and laboratory evidence suggestive of spontaneous HLH resolution on day 10. The diagnosis was considered to be transient HLH triggered by HHV6 infection. Immediately after hospital discharge the patient developed a diffuse vesicular rash from which varicella-zoster virus (VZV) DNA was detected by PCR. This occurred 20 days after receiving the varicella vaccine. The patient was treated with acyclovir for 5 days (20 mg/kg every 6 h) without complication. There was no attempt to ascertain by molecular testing whether VZV was the vaccine strain. However the patient had no exposure to individuals with chickenpox or shingles at home or in hospital. Based on molecular typing of rash-associated virus in post-marketing varicella vaccine surveillance in two countries, the timing of this rash was more consistent with vaccine-strain varicella (median onset 17-21 days post-vaccination) than with wild type varicella (median interval: 7-8 days post-vaccination). Thus on a balance of probabilities, the patient likely experienced dissemination of vaccine-strain VZV rather than wild type varicella. At 14 months of age, immunological work up was undertaken which revealed a polyclonal increase in IgG, protective antibody levels against measles, VZV, diphtheria, and tetanus and normal lymphocyte subset analysis. Immunophenotyping results, (patient II:3) showed total lymphocytes was 3,600 (normal range: 1600-6,700), CD3+ CD4+ was 1,008 (normal range: 1,000-4,600), CD3+ CD8+ was 756 (normal range: 400-2,100), CD3 was 1,368 (normal range: 600-2,700), CD19+ CD3- CD56+ was 216 (normal range: 200-1,200), IgG (mg/dL) was 1,170 (normal range: 300-900), IgG1 was 979 mg/dL (normal range: 160-562), IgG2 was 218 mg/dL (normal range: 24-98), IgG3 was 90 mg/dL (normal range: 17-64), IgG4 was 201 mg/dL (normal range: 0-22), IgM was 63 mg/dL (normal range: 15-70), IgA was 40 mg/dL (normal range: 40-160), IgE was 6 IU/ml (normal range: 0.62-1.6), Tetanus IgG was 4.5 IU/ml (normal range: more than 0.1), Diphtheria IgG was 0.8 IU/ml (normal range: more than 0.1), Measles IgG was more than 300 AU/ml (normal range: more than or equal to 30) and VZV IgG was 1033 Index units (normal range: more than or equal to 135). At 14 months of age, the patient had pulmonary consolidation and fever for 4 days associated with rhinovirus/enterovirus. At 15 months of age, the patient had rhinovirus/enterovirus upper respiratory tract infection with fever for 7 days. At 17 months of age, the patient had suppurative otitis media with fever. At 24 months of age, the patient had febrile parainfluenza virus type 3 upper respiratory tract infection. At 25 months of age, the patient had mixed upper respiratory tract infection with parainfluenza virus type 3, human metapneumovirus, and rhinovirus/enterovirus. At 26 months of age, the patient had upper respiratory tract infection with rhinovirus/enterovirus, with 5 days of fever up to 39.3 degree C and development of lower extremity papular and urticarial rash. Now 3 years of age, her physical growth and developmental milestones had been normal. Further live vaccines had been withheld. Prophylactic immunoglobulin therapy was not felt to be indicated. This case has been considered as serious due to hospitalization. The author commented, "This case informs understanding of the function of STAT2 in both antiviral immunity and immunoregulation. STAT2 is unique among human STATs, by virtue of both its narrow spectrum of activity (within IFN-I/III pathways) and its direct participation in both positive and negative regulation. Defining the molecular and clinical consequences of STAT2 variants provides not only clinically relevant information, but also fundamental insight into the involvement of STAT2, and IFNI/III more generally, in human immunity. It should be noted that severe IAV displays incomplete clinical penetrance in patients with mutated TLR3, IRF7, IRF9, or STAT2. This is not unexpected, since in the context of defects of pathogen defence there are multiple factors that likely contribute to variable expressivity, including: variable pathogen exposure, infecting dose, prior vaccination and compensation by adaptive immunity. Disease caused by live-attenuated parenteral viral vaccines continues to serve as a clear signal of compromised IFNAR signaling. Another novel observation in this case is the occurrence of clinical varicella following VZV immunization, which has not previously been described in STAT2 deficiency. The implication is that vaccine-strain VZV may, like other live-attenuated vaccines such as MMR, be effectively controlled by innate IFNs in vivo, consistent with a previous report of VZV dissemination in a child with IRF9 deficiency. Regrettably in our case, molecular analysis was not undertaken at the time of varicella diagnosis to definitively prove the vaccine origin of VZV, nor was material stored to enable retrospective analysis. It is also notable that dissemination of MMR virus was not identified in this case, despite a suggestive temporal association between administration of MMR and the onset of clinical disease. MMR dissemination is strongly associated with defects of IFN-I/III immunity, but is not inevitable. Again, it should be noted that in our case, blood and/or mucosal samples were not analyzed by PCR for MMR viral detection, and no clinical material was available to retrospectively test. Therefore occult MMR viral replication cannot be excluded as a potential contribution to HLH. The capacity of IFN gamma to compensate for antiviral activity in vitro might suggest a potential therapeutic role in controlling viral replication, however this approach may come at a cost of enhancing hyperinflammation. There have been clinical reports of responsiveness to IVIG or steroids, although in our case the hyperinflammation resolved without specific treatment. More work is needed to dissect the pathomechanism and inform therapeutic strategies." The author concluded, "In summary, this case significantly expands our clinical understanding of STAT2 deficiency. As the first report of life-threatening IAV in STAT2 deficiency, we can now add STAT2 to the list of genes implicated in this phenotype - a list that increasingly emphasizes the importance of IFN-I/III. We also report the first instance of disseminated vaccine-strain VZV in STAT2-deficiency, suggesting a role for innate IFNs in control of live-attenuated VZV vaccines. Finally, as only the second report of HLH in a patient with STAT2-deficiency, this case strengthens the notion that STAT2-deficient patients are vulnerable to hyperinflammation, motivating further investigation of the underlying mechanism(s) and highlighting the enduring capacity of monogenic diseases to uncover novel areas for scientific exploration."

received on feb 9th their 3rd dose of pediarix/ On 4/20/2021 received/ engerix; On 4/20/2021 received/ DOSE 1( 4TH DOSE OF DTAP AND POLIO) of kinrix.; On 4/20/2021 received/ DOSE 1( 4TH DOSE OF DTAP AND POLIO) of kinrix.; This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of extra dose administered in a 9-month-old male patient who received HBV (Engerix B) (batch number YL2L3, expiry date 14th December 2021) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included hepatitis B vaccine pre-filled syringe device (Engerix B Pre-Filled Syringe Device) injection syringe for prophylaxis, DTPa-IPV (Kinrix) (batch number YZ97N, expiry date 26th August 2022) for prophylaxis and dtpa-ipv vaccine pre-filled syringe device (Kinrix Pre-Filled Syringe Device) injection syringe for prophylaxis.   Concomitant products included DTPa-HBV-IPV (Pediarix).   On 20th April 2021, the patient received the 4th dose of Engerix B, Engerix B Pre-Filled Syringe Device, the 1st dose of Kinrix and Kinrix Pre-Filled Syringe Device. On 20th April 2021, unknown after receiving Engerix B and Engerix B Pre-Filled Syringe Device and not applicable after receiving Kinrix and Kinrix Pre-Filled Syringe Device, the patient experienced extra dose administered, inappropriate age at vaccine administration and inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered. On an unknown date, the outcome of the extra dose administered, inappropriate age at vaccine administration and inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered were unknown.   This report is made by GSK without prejudice and does not imply any admission or liability for the incident or its consequences.  Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received 3rd dose of Pediarix on 9th February 2021. The patient received Engerix B, this becames an extra dose of Hepatitis B. The patient received Kinrix as a 4th dose of Dtap and IPV, which led to inappropriate age at vaccine administration and inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered. The reported batch number for Kinrix was YZNZN, which was updated to YZ97N as per sales datasheet. The reporter consented to follow-up.

scan confirmed a stroke; foot was dragging; nurse forgot to reconstitute with the Shingrix antigen and injected just the Shingrix adjuvant; injected just the Shingrix adjuvant into an unknown arm; This case was reported by a consumer and described the occurrence of stroke in a 75-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included type ii diabetes mellitus and fibromyalgia.   On 13th April 2021, the patient received Shingrix (intramuscular) and the 1st dose of Shingrix. On 13th April 2021, not applicable after receiving Shingrix and unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced inappropriate dose of vaccine administered and inappropriate preparation of medication. On 15th April 2021, the patient experienced stroke (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and leg dragging (serious criteria hospitalization). On an unknown date, the outcome of the stroke was not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the leg dragging, inappropriate dose of vaccine administered and inappropriate preparation of medication were unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the stroke and leg dragging to be related to Shingrix and Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows:  The caller was the daughter of the patient. On the 1st Shingrix injection, the nurse forgot to reconstitute with the Shingrix antigen and injected just the Shingrix adjuvant, which led to inappropriate dose of vaccine administered and inappropriate preparation of medication. The Shingrix 1st injection was administered in unknown arm and after realizing her mistake, nurse reconstituted the Shingrix vaccine correctly and injected it into the patient's right arm. On 15th April 2021, the patients foot was dragging and she was transported to the emergency room (ER) and CT scan confirmed a stroke. The reporter was waiting for the results of the MRI that was done on 19th April 2021. The caller reports her mother was nursing home resident and the nurse called the caller to let her know her mother received both an injection of the adjuvant for Shingrix and a Shingrix vaccine.   The reporter does not give permission to contact the HCP.      The reporter did not consent to follow up.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Very serious reaction to the first / dose / she was sick; Very serious reaction to the first / dose / she was / with flu-like symptoms; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of sickness in a 74-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included shingles (on an unknown dates, patient had shingles twice in her lifetime when she was younger). Previously administered products included Shingles vaccine with an associated reaction of no adverse event (received live shingles vaccine on an uknown date and did not have any side effects). Concurrent medical conditions included drug hypersensitivity and chemical sensitivity. Concomitant products included benadryl (nos) (Benadryl).   In August 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced sickness (serious criteria other: Serious as per reporter ) and influenza-like symptoms (serious criteria other: Serious as per reporter). Shingrix was discontinued. On an unknown date, the outcome of the sickness and influenza-like symptoms were recovered/resolved.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the sickness and influenza-like symptoms to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The case was reported by the patient for herself. The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient had both the shingles incidents before she received the Shingrix vaccine. The patient received the live shingles vaccine before she had ever received the first Shingrix dose. The patient reported that she has had a medication/chemical sensitivity condition before she received the first Shingrix dose. It was not a full-blown allergic reaction, but it did have an effect on her. She expanded on this sensitivity by stating that she had a delayed reaction to allergy shots which include flu-like symptoms in the morning and which used to get worse at night.  The patient stated that this sick feeling with flu-like symptoms did not start right after the first Shingrix dose but that it was a delayed reaction. She did not have any anaphylactic shock or hives.  The patient never received her 2nd Shingrix dose because she had a very serious reaction to the 1st dose.  The patient further described this reaction by stating that she was sick with flu-like symptoms for three weeks.  The patient declined to provide her date of birth or her full address and was unable to provide the dosage, lot number or expiration date of the Shingrix dose she received, and the full address, email address, or fax number of her physician.  The reporter consented to follow up.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Shingles (on an unknown dates, patient had shingles twice in her lifetime when she was younger)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: received a Shingrix dose on the 4th of August 2020; This case was reported by a pharmacist via call center representative and described the occurrence of incomplete course of vaccination in a adult patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Previously administered products included Shingles vaccine (1st dose received in 2016).   On 4th August 2020, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced incomplete course of vaccination. On an unknown date, the outcome of the incomplete course of vaccination was unknown.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not applicable for this report. The age group was not reported but was captured as an adult as per vaccine indication.  The patient had received first dose of Shingles vaccine in 2016.  The reporter did not have any further details at the time of the call. On further follow-up, the health care professional who was not the same pharmacist stated that the patient received a Shingrix dose on the 4th of August, 2020. The health care professional would be receiving the patient on the reporting date in the afternoon, and would talk with the patient about the vaccination because the information they had was not clear.  The reporter consented to follow-up via email.  Note: As Shingrix came into market in 2017, dose given in 2020 was considered as 1st dose and hence incomplete course of vaccination event was coded conservatively until further clarification received on follow-up.

suffered spontaneous contractions / had a central line placed; tachycardic / (intubation removed after) and hypotensive; hypoxemia; Chronic bronquitis; never recovered pulmonary activity and died / Respiratory failure with hypoxemia; Elevated MI and shock; Elevated MI and shock; kidney problem / Diagnosed with membranous glomerulonephritis / worsened /hospitalized after getting worse; kidney problem / Diagnosed with membranous glomerulonephritis / worsened /hospitalized after getting worse; extremely ill kidneys shut down / developed acute renal failure; tubular necrosis; Metabolic encephalopathy (due to hyponatremia and anoxia); anoxia; Thrombocytopenia; hypotension (secondary to hypovolemia). /hypotensive; secondary to hypovolemia; Rash on the lower extremities; Decreased fluid and nourishment intake due to inability to eat and drink; Decreased fluid / due to inability to eat and drink; Hyponatremia; Transaminitis; Increased /creatinine; Increased BUN and creatinine; malaise; flu like symptoms / flu like illness; viral-like symptoms; myalgia; fever / Fever 103.9�F; multiorgan failure; rapidly decompensated with seizure; This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of respiratory failure in a 62-year-old male patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   The patient's past medical history included biopsy (had a biopsy on February 2018.). Previously administered products included prednisone, ciclosporin, immunosuppressive therapy (had exacerbation of the problem and was treated with immunosuppressive therapy using rituximab twice) and rituximab. Concurrent medical conditions included renal disorder (had long standing kidney problems) and glomerulonephritis membranous (diagnosed with membranous glomerulonephritis). Concomitant products included rituximab.   On 22nd May 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix. In May 2018, less than 2 weeks after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced seizure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and multi-organ failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant). On 22nd May 2018, the patient experienced influenza like illness (serious criteria hospitalization), viral infection (serious criteria hospitalization), myalgia (serious criteria hospitalization), fever (serious criteria hospitalization) and malaise (serious criteria hospitalization). On 26th May 2018, the patient experienced thrombocytopenia (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), hypotension (serious criteria hospitalization), hypovolemia (serious criteria hospitalization), rash (serious criteria hospitalization), unable to eat (serious criteria hospitalization), fluid intake reduced (serious criteria hospitalization), hyponatremia (serious criteria hospitalization), transaminitis (serious criteria hospitalization), creatinine increased (serious criteria hospitalization) and blood urea nitrogen increased (serious criteria hospitalization). On 29th May 2018, the patient experienced respiratory failure (serious criteria death, hospitalization and GSK medically significant), myocardial infarction (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), cardiogenic shock (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), glomerulonephritis membranous (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), condition aggravated (serious criteria hospitalization), acute renal failure (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), tubular necrosis (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), metabolic encephalopathy (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), anoxia (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant), hypoxemia (serious criteria hospitalization and GSK medically significant) and chronic bronchitis (serious criteria hospitalization). On 30th May 2018, the patient experienced tachycardia (serious criteria hospitalization) and muscle contractions involuntary (serious criteria hospitalization). On 30th May 2018, the outcome of the respiratory failure was fatal. On an unknown date, the outcome of the myocardial infarction, cardiogenic shock, glomerulonephritis membranous, condition aggravated, acute renal failure, thrombocytopenia, tubular necrosis, metabolic encephalopathy, anoxia, seizure, hypoxemia, multi-organ failure, chronic bronchitis, hypotension, tachycardia, hypovolemia, muscle contractions involuntary, influenza like illness, viral infection, myalgia, fever, rash, malaise, unable to eat, fluid intake reduced, hyponatremia, transaminitis, creatinine increased and blood urea nitrogen increased were unknown. The patient died on 30th May 2018. The reported cause of death was respiratory failure. An autopsy was performed.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the respiratory failure, myocardial infarction, cardiogenic shock, glomerulonephritis membranous, condition aggravated, acute renal failure, thrombocytopenia, tubular necrosis, metabolic encephalopathy, anoxia, seizure, hypoxemia, multi-organ failure, chronic bronchitis, hypotension, tachycardia, hypovolemia, muscle contractions involuntary, influenza like illness, viral infection, myalgia, fever, rash, malaise, unable to eat, fluid intake reduced, hyponatremia, transaminitis, creatinine increased and blood urea nitrogen increased to be related to Shingrix.  Additional details were provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported. The patient had long standing kidney problems and was various drugs for the past 20 years. The patient had last Rituximab treatment on 16th May 2018. As per MD (Doctor of Medicine) insistence patient got Shingrix vaccine. The patient experienced flu like symptoms, myalgia, fever and malaise and his condition worsened. On 26th May 2018, the patient was hospitalized after getting worse. The patient got extremely ill, kidneys shut down, there was hypotension (secondary to hypovolemia), decreased fluid and nourishment intake due to inability to eat and drink, fever 103.9 degree Fahrenheit, rash on the lower extremities, thrombocytopenia, hyponatremia decreased sodium, blood urea nitrogen increased and creatinine increased and transaminitis. Initial hospital could not do dialysis due to lack of equipment and was transferred to reporters hospital with a diagnose of membranous glomerulonephritis. On 29th May 2018, the patient was transferred to reporter's hospital and patient died in less than 24 hours. The patient developed acute renal failure with tubular necrosis, respiratory failure with hypoxemia, chronic bronchitis (found in reporter's hospital), metabolic encephalopathy (due to hyponatremia and anoxia), elevated MI (myocardial infarction) and shock. The patient had viral-like symptoms, tests for several common viruses came negative. As per physician notes patient rapidly decompensated with seizure and multiorgan failure, questionable meningitis versus immune response; pathologist (reporter) confirms patient did not have meningitis. On 30th May 2018, the patient was declared DNR (do-not-resuscitate) by family and later became asystolic, suffered spontaneous contractions and had a central line placed. The patient became tachycardic and hypotensive and was removed from intubation and 2 minutes later never recovered pulmonary activity and died. The health care professional was performing autopsy on a patient. No vaccine administration information available to reporter. The reporter consented to follow-up. Concomitant products included PREDNISONE for Pain and Rash, METHYLPREDNISOLONE (MEDROL DOSEPAK) for an unknown indication.    On 17-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient experienced POLYMYALGIA RHEUMATICA (Polymyalgia rheumatica) (seriousness criterion medically significant), PAIN (Pain became more consistent), PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Arm pain/pain is in his arm), ARTHRALGIA (Pain in shoulders), HYPOKINESIA (Could not lift arm), ARTHRALGIA (Left hip hurt), INFLAMMATION (Inflammatory reaction), TREMOR (Shaking), GAIT DISTURBANCE (he could not get out of bed, was shaking, and used a cane to walk), ARTHRALGIA (Joint pain) and PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Pain in legs got worse). At the time of the report, POLYMYALGIA RHEUMATICA (Polymyalgia rheumatica), PAIN (Pain became more consistent), PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Arm pain/pain is in his arm), ARTHRALGIA (Pain in shoulders), ARTHRALGIA (Left hip hurt), ARTHRALGIA (Joint pain) and PAIN IN EXTREMITY (Pain in legs got worse) had not resolved and HYPOKINESIA (Could not lift arm), INFLAMMATION (Inflammatory reaction), TREMOR (Shaking) and GAIT DISTURBANCE (he could not get out of bed, was shaking, and used a cane to walk) outcome was unknown. Since the patient's first dose of the Moderna vaccine, he had not been on prednisone the whole time but was recently put on a Medrol pack. He was diagnosed with polymyalgia rheumatica as his pain became more consistent after the first dose of the vaccine. His pain is in his arm and shoulders, his left hip hurt and he was not able to lift his arm all the way up.  The patient believed that the vaccine may had caused an inflammatory reaction that aggravated his pain that was present before the vaccine. The patient also stated there was a time that he was not able to get out of bed, he was shaking, and had to use a cane to walk. He says he never had joint pain, only stiffness when waking up and soreness in his hip and leg that was painful. After the vaccine, his arm hurt to the extent he could not sleep on it and the pain in his legs had worsened. He makes it very clear he had a lot of pain prior to the vaccine, but the pain he was experiencing now is more consistent. Concomitant medications included bupropion for anxiety depression and omeprazole for acid reflux, both ongoing.  The patient previously received flu and tetanus on unspecified dates for immunization and both experienced hard red welt on arm (welt was hard and lasted for 5-7 days). The patient reported no side effects for 12 hours, but a little soreness at injection site on 17Mar2021 at 20:00 (8:00 PM). Her arm wasn't heavy, but she had an awareness of the soreness.  She has had life-long anxiety and depression. Several weeks ago (on 26Mar2021), her anxiety reared up, and it could have been due to a family situation. On the 9th day after the first shot, she was having a therapy appointment on the phone and talking about her anxiety, and she got a stiff neck, like an iron claw (26Mar2021 at 10:00 am). It lasted for a couple of 5 minutes and she laid down on the couch then on the floor.  Her therapist said to call 911. Emergency medical technicians came to her house and they said all of her numbers looked good.  She went to the hospital, and was in the emergency room for several hours, but she only remembers one hour of it.  She also had diarrhea and nausea on 26Mar2021 at 11:30, and it felt like Dumping Syndrome, that one can have from a gastric bypass. She was only aware for one hour at that point and blacked out (on 26Mar2021). With regards to nausea, she mostly saw bile in the bag, all she had that day was a protein drink. She was back home and the next day, she did not remember how she got home. She hasn't had blackouts anymore but feels it may be from heightened anxiety. Her doctor felt like she should have an MRI. Her heart and all of her numbers looked good, as the emergency medical technicians said. Her primary doctor recommended her to get the second shot.  She had cancelled the second shot for this week, and she has rescheduled it for another date.  She was afraid that she will black out again, after the next vaccine, and is not sure if that is how her anxiety manifested. The main reasons she is calling is that she had no concerns of side effects prior to the vaccine, and a couple of her neighbors said they had read about side effects of the vaccine, but she was not worried.  When the patient started to read about side effects of the vaccine, she understood that on the 10th day, the vaccine starts to be in a person's system and that maybe is why she didn't have initial side effects, but then she had side effects several days later because the vaccine was in her body.  By day 10, the vaccine is in effect in the body and she is nervous. Her second vaccine is scheduled on 26Apr2021. The patient would like to know if there is any information on people that have had a gastric bypass. The patient has no prior vaccinations within 4 weeks. The events resulted in emergency room visit (except nervous). The patient recovered from soreness at injection site on 18Mar2021; recovered from diarrhea, nausea,  felt like Dumping Syndrome on 26Mar2021; recovered from stiff neck on 26Mar2021 at 10:05am; recovered from constipation on 02Apr2021; and recovered from no appetite and lost 6 pounds on unspecified dates. An as ER nurse for 30 years, she can tell his level of pain was more than 10 on a pain scale. At the doctor's appoint he did tell (name) how bad the migraines were. He was really highly ranked in the military so his pain tolerance was pretty high, to see him double over with headache was unbelievable. Treatment was Aimovig injection, it's a once a month injection, but she understood that it can take up to weeks for it to actually work. shingles/herpes zoster-viral infection of the periocular and facial region; cornea keratitis herpes zoster; postherpetic polyneuropathy; Information has been received from a lawyer regarding a case in litigation which referred to a patient (pt) of unknown gender and age. Information regarding concomitant medications, concurrent conditions or medical history was not provided. On 28-JUN-2017, the pt was vaccinated with zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) for its intended purpose: the prevention of shingles (herpes zoster) and for routine health maintenance (exact dose, dose number, route of administration, anatomical site of vaccination, lot number and expiration date were not provided). Afterwards, on an unknown date (reported as shortly after receiving zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine), the pt suffered recurrent rash on the side of her head, face, hair line, nose and eye, accompanied by extreme pain on the right sde of head, scalp, and eye, and blurred vision. The pt was diagnosed with Herpes Zoster-viral infection of the periocular and facial region and shingles (herpes zoster), cornea keratitis herpes zoster (ophthalmic herpes zoster), and postherpetic polyneuropathy (post herpetic neuralgia). As a direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) vaccine, the pt sustained severe and permanent personal injuries; the pt's symptoms had resulted in physical limitations not present prior to using zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX). The pt also experienced mental and emotional distress due to resulting physical limitations and seriousness of pt's condition. Further, the pt had suffered serious, progressive, permanent, and incurable injuries, as well as significant conscious pain and suffering, mental anguish, emotional distress, loss of enjoyment of life, physical impairment and injury. Finally, as direct and proximate result of zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX), the pt had suffered and incurred damages, including medical expenses; the loss of accumulations; and other economic and non-economic damages. The outcome of the events was considered as not recovered. The causal relationship between the events and zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) was assessed as related.  Herpes zoster, post herpetic neuralgia and ophthalmic herpes zoster were considered as disabling events by the reporter.   Upon internal review, the event ophthalmic herpes zoster was determined to be medically significant.

erythema and pruritis to left arm around immediate site of the vaccine, monitored for 30min and appeared to improve - erythema almost completely resolved, no rash presented anywhere else and pt had no respiratory symptoms and felt fine. Recommended Benadryl 25-50mg if itching persisted and advised follow-up for additional care if symptoms worsened. Called to follow up the next day and check on the pt, had initially improved but then worsened and had redness and hives to both arms, then to back, neck and chest. pt took Claritin (about an hour or more after benadryl) and symptoms improved over several hours - they did not seek additional medical attention and today pt is back to baseline.  She never had any wheezing, coughing, swelling or difficulty swallowing - no respiratory symptoms at all. Given the rash worsened to chest and back and symptoms took >4hrs to resolve, recommended she NOT return for her second dose due to increased risk of a more severe allergic reaction. Notified PCP and recommended f/u with PCP for any additional questions or concerns.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my first shot at 4:15PM on Sunday 04/25/21. The dose was administered into my right arm. Within 30sec-1min I started feeling pressure wave slowly spreading from my right arm and traveling to my right shoulder blade and neck. Within few minutes I developed neck pain like I pulled a muscle on my right side. 1-2min later I started having muted hearing in my right ear and felt heaviness on my head. within 10-20mins my left ear was impacted as well. (hearing issues lasted about 30mins-1hr). Also, within first 10-15 minutes my face felt swollen and heavy, but it was not visually swollen. Once I took my mask off in the car, I had red/pink marbled rash on my skin on the area that the mask was covering. I haven't had any face rash from this mask before.  I asked the vaccine site staff if the back and neck symptoms are normal, she gave me a blank stare and nodded her head. Additionally, after first 10 minutes my left thigh muscle started cramping and involuntarily moving for a few minutes, quickly followed by feeling of pulling nerve in my right thigh. That lasted around a minute and suddenly moved upwards and hit my back with sharp pain like radiculitis. Every slight change of move felt like sharp sting. I was still in the recovery area, but I had trouble staying in the sitting position. We went home and back pain developed into crippling pain within 30 mins-1hr after the shot. I could do less and less. By 1 hr I was only able to lay flat in my bed, unable to sit. Bending over would not be possible because of tightness and sharp pain. I spent the next day in bed and barely tiptoed to the bathroom when needed, holding onto the furniture and walls. It has been more than 48 hours and I still can't bend or wash my hands. I can wash one at a time. Today I can sit, so my back improved since yesterday, but my moves are limited and I feel some pain in my back when I walk. I can't sit for too long and sitting down or getting up hurts.

On day 4 following dose 2 of Moderna series, pt developed fever, chills, fatigue, malaise and self-medicated with ibuprofen and acetaminophen. After a "few" days of feeling unwell despite treatment, presented to ER and was found to have AKI, hyponatremia, and thrombocytopenia. Over the course of several days rapidly deteriorated and developed MSOF, including liver failure, DIC, respiratory failure requiring intubation, and shock requiring pressors. Workup for VTE, including V/Q scan, LE dopplers, and head CT negative for thrombosis. Ferritin was found to be highly elevated (12,000) suggestive of hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH). Per ER report, marrow positive for hemophagocytosis on smear. At time of report, transferred to Cancer Center for HLH treatment, currently in ICU, intubated, sedated, and on pressors. PF4 antibody pending.

Client received her first Pfizer dose of  0.3mL in left deltoid on 04/27/21 at 09:32am with lot number EW0179 expiring on 08/31/2021. Client who is 32-year-old female with no race or ethnicity was disclosed, was brought to EMT station by ancillary staff after complaining of tingling in her toes. Client remained alert and tracking with her eyes and appeared in no apparent distress. Client had a chief complaint of tingling in her toes bilaterally at 10:01am on 04/27/2021. Client stated that she completed her 15-minute observation and was walking to her car, when she noticed tingling in her toes bilaterally and returned to the site/EMT station. toes that was painless and localized. Client's airway, breathing and circulation were intact. Client's initial set of vitals was blood pressure 132/84, pulse 80, alert and oriented to person, place, event and time, respiration 16, eyes equal and reactive to light and lung sounds clear bilaterally. EMT  was unable to obtain an SPO2 due to client's acrylic fingernails. Client noted that she had spoken to her doctor recently and her doctor stated to her that she had "poor circulation," but did not specify any diagnosis. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received my vaccine in the left arm in the mid-afternoon on Sunday and experienced little discomfort the rest of the day with some soreness in the arm before bed. My arm was sore to the touch and in the late afternoon i noticed i had a mild rash across the back of my arm  starting below my deltoid muscle and spread out and down close to my elbow.  It was not a bright red but the area was remarkably sensitive, so much so that i felt i should report the reaction because ive never had a noticeable reaction to a vaccine so i became mildly alarmed. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt received dose #1 of Moderna on 1/20/2021 at clinic. On 1/24/2021, developed self reported fatigue and sleep disturbances with pruritis. Sought no medical care. Routine labs were obtained on 2/23 which demonstrated new-onset transaminitis and hyperferritinemia (ALT 2366, AST 1260, alk phos 362, ferritin 32,000) and was admitted to hospital for evaluation. No etiology for acute liver failure identified, including comprehensive evaluation for viral hepatitis and other common causes of hepatitis common after transplant. Concern raised for hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH) due to extreme hyperferritinemia, although bone marrow biopsy negative. Ultimately transferred to another hospital for further care at patient's request. No specific treatment was given and transaminitis ultimately resolved. Soluble IL-2 receptor (CD25) level checked on 3/2, at time of admission, markedly elevated at 2338.6, consistent with diagnosis of HLH. Pt discharged on 3/5. Ultimately readmitted on 3/9 and found to have rapidly progressive Legionella pneumonia and died on 3/16. At approx 1800, while inactive and sitting, I lost vision in my left eye.  Since I am fairly recently post partum (delivered 3/20/21), I took my blood pressure as a precaution.  My initial reading was 161/108 with repeat 5min later 156/106.  I was instructed to go to the nearest ER.  My BPs there were 171/86 and 166/96.  Labs and diagnostic imaging were performed and I rec'd IV fluids, Reglan, and IV Tylenol.  I was discharged around 0045 with a diagnosis of Migraine Headache.  I woke up on Tuesday 4/27 with a worsening headache.  My BP was 148/91, 141/100 and 130/100 throughout the morning.  I was seen by my chiropractor in an attempt to resolve the neck pain around noon, my BP afterwards was 149/99 142/97-No resolution of headache.  At this point I was instructed to go to Medical Facility for further testing and admission to the women?s services unit.  My BP just prior to admission was 146/107. I had a syncope event while trimming tree limbs from a platform 8 feet off the ground. I suffered 3 compression fractured vertebrae when I blacked out getting ready to get off onto a ladder to get down. No advance warning, no dizziness, no vision impairment, nothing except a sore knee when I bent over to kneel on the platform in preparation to get on the ladder. It was like someone turned off a light switch and then turned it back on after I was on the ground. Don't remember even getting down or a fall, but I was down on the ground. When I went to get back on ladder to retrieve my equipment I could not lift my leg due to pain and felt like I had a pulled groin muscle. Laid down and could not get up.

Client received the COVID vaccine (Pfizer dose 2, lot #EW0179, expiration 4/28/2021) at 1525. Client reported "a spot of numbness" on his tongue at 1544, RNs, PHN, responded at that time. The client's subjective symptoms were similar to what happened 30 minutes after his first dose, per the client, and they resolved after 1 hour that time. The client did not appear to be in distress, had no visible swelling or redness on his face, tongue, or lips, and complained of no shortness of breath. O2 was 98% and heart rate was 86. The client takes no medications and has no medical history. The client's only allergy was a childhood allergy to bees with a localized reaction, that has since resolved as an adult. At 1550, the client stated that the numbness had started to improve and deferred benadryl at that time. At 1553, the client's blood pressure was 130/100 using the automatic cuff. At 1556, the client's repeat blood pressure was 127/98, with an O2 of 97, respiratory rate of 14, and heart rate of 81. At 1605, the client's blood pressure was 136/115 on the automatic cuff, with O2 98 and heart rate 87. The client had a bright affect and was conversational with staff. At 1615, the client stated he felt "good" and was comfortable driving home. The final vital signs for the client were blood pressure 140/97, heart rate 88, and O2 98%. Education provided regarding v-safe, primary care follow up, emergency management, and AMR activation.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: first vaccine-started within 3 hrs of injection. Intense muscle and joint pain for 48 hours. second vaccine-started within 30 minutes of injection=dizziness. I then had to take 4 nitroglycerin pills, 0.4mg each ( 1 every 5 minutes) before the chest pains stopped. Then after that, all of the side effects ceased except for tiredness which lasted another 24 hours. Note: I have nitroglycerin on hand since I had a heart attack in 2001. I only occasionally need to take it, not more then 1x/year, sometimes I can go for several years without taking any. If I had not had any on hand, I would have gone to the nearest ER.  Note-I have continued to have shakiness off and on about 3x/week which is still persisting.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At 8:00 pm after receiving the vaccine at 3:00 pm I started with chills.  Went to bed to try to sleep and rest.  Then this tingling feeling started.  It would happen at different places through out my body.  It would be in my arms, hands, chest, head, legs, feet, side or everywhere.  Then it would be in just one area for a period of time.  Next morning I started to get electrical shock feelings on top of the tingling.  By Saturday I was in bed as my legs felt too weak to walk.  The tingling was mostly just in my legs at this point.  The electrical shock feeling was still coming and going but the tingling never stopped in my legs and feet.  It would wake me up out of a dead sleep.  This kept happening and I went to the doctor Monday morning.  I had started to improve some.  Still weak in my legs, tingling and some shock feelings.  The doctor felt it was a nerve response to the vaccine and would pass after a few more days.  It has improved as I am able to be up and doing things now.  Unfortunately the tingling hasn?t stop at all in my right legs.  Especially my last three toes and they hurt, burn and just feel odd most all the time.  I still get shock feelings at times in that foot and some times other places but not as often.  I still get tingling in the side of my head at times still also.  Now today 4/27/21 my right hand is hurting and hard to move.  My toes feel like they are curling under at times and they are perfectly straight.  I still have a few nights where the shock feeling with wake me up in the night.  Tomorrow will be two weeks from my vaccine.  I wondered if this has happened to others, when does it stop, and should I get the second vaccine?  I do not want to go back to the point where it was hard to walk even and the pain.
LAB_DATA: Went for a consultation and examine.  Felt was a nerve response to vaccine and give time.
OTHER_MEDS: Zoloft Omeprazole Multi Vitamin  Flonase Claritin  IUD

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within  a couple hours of dose, I was feeling really awful as if I had the flu with a pounding headache, all of my body hurt, naseau as if I was going to vomit, and my arm was really hurting. It progressively got worse throughout the day with feeling hot and cold so I took an Extra Strength Tylenol in case of fever. I went to bed around 10 pm and woke up out of a dead sleep around 2 am feeling like I was having trouble breathing. All of my body hurt, I was freezing cold and shaking with chills, and really dizzy and my head was still pounding. My arm where the injection site was also felt like it was burning. I thought I would take a hot bath to ease the chills and go back to sleep, but when I got out my naseau was even worse, my head was really hurting, and I began getting really dizzy sitting on the floor. I called my roommate in and said, "I think something's wrong. I'm going to vomit or black out" and that's the last thing I remember. I did black out and my roommate said I had what looked like three seizures and he called 911. I was shaking for several hours after that at the hospital.  It is now the same day, 4.27.2021, 9 am and I am home from the hospital. I still feel weak, dizzy and nauseaous and my entire body hurts.
LAB_DATA: At 4 am Tuesday morning 4/27/2021, EMS was called to be taken to the hospital. Resulting in CT scan, chest xray, EKG.   Staff at the hospital said they were not responsible for reporting adverse reactions of the vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: Birth control, Extra Strength Tylenol at 2 pm, 1/2 of muscle relaxer at 8 pm
