Patient had felt nervous prior to getting her 2nd shot. I asked if she had every had any serious reactions from previous medicines or vaccines, she stated "no". I then asked how she did after her first shot and she said ok. While waiting her 15 min in the observation area she alerted us that she was feeling extremely hot. We brought her back into the IMZ booth and had her sit in the chair and turned a fan in her direction. I sat down with her an asked her questions and kept her talking to try to calm her down. She stated that she felt as if the chair was swaying a little. We laid out a yoga mat on the floor in the booth, had her lay down and elevate her feet in a chair. She began to get upset and I asked if she had anyone with her, she was able to open her phone and gave me permission to call her family member. Family member came in the store and was able to help calm her down. We gave her some water and had her rest. I monitored her pulse and face/lip color. She became a little flushed. She was able to leave on her own accord, I did walk out with her to ensure she made it safely. I called 2 hours later to check on her and she stated she was feeling better, less dizzy, but just a little tired.

I don't recall the last time I was so ill and in pain.  Did not lessen at all throughout the day.  Took Advil 3 times that day.  I tried to go to work but couldn't stay.  Had to take a sick day.  Went to bed at 9:00pm and slept until 9:30am.  I usually sleep 6-7 hours.  I broke out into a sweat multiple times through the night.  The following day, I woke up much better but still weak.  By the end of that day, I was probably back to 75%.  I was back to normal on Sunday.  It was horrible experience and will unfortunately prevent me  from getting the vaccine annually.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I have had a prolonged period and then it started again halfway through the cycle  I have been on Yaz birth control for almost 10 years. My period is always very regular, starting on Tuesday and ending on Friday. It is always also light. This month it started as regular on April 6 (same day as first dose of Pfizer vaccine) but did not end until the following Wednesday, April 14. It was heavier than normal. Then my period started again on April 22 and is still on-going (today is April 27). I am not stressed in any way, not about the vaccine or any other life circumstances, I am not sick, I have not had anything else different in my life other than taking the Covid Pfizer vaccine on April 6. I am not pregnant. Nothing else is weird with my body. I did just get the 2nd Covid Pfizer vaccine shot about 30 minutes ago and felt that the benefits of the vaccine outweigh the inconvenience of this very odd period cycle, but I definitely wanted to report it to help the data and to help other women who may be going through the same thing.  I spoke with my primary care provider who wasn't able to find any data about it in the Pfizer vaccine side effects list, because it wasn't looked at when the initial studies were done. He referred me to an OB/GYN but that appointment isn't for another couple of weeks.
ALLERGIES: Allergic to amixicillan. Haven't taken this since 2014.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 1.5-2 hours after receiving the Pfizer-BioNtech COVID-19 vaccine (lot ER2613,) at approximately 8:40 am on 4/26/21, I started having mild jaw pain. At about 4 pm that afternoon the jaw pain worsened to the point where I was unable to chew without pain. Around this time, I started having chills. Immediately pre- and post- vaccine I was alternating Tylenol and Motrin every 6 hours. At around 11 pm that night I was experiencing chills and myalgias. Between 1-2 am on 4/27/21, I started experiencing right-sided facial drooping. I found it difficult to open my right eye and my entire face felt numb. The jaw pain was even more severe with these symptoms, and I had to pry my right eye open by tugging at my eyebrow region. Given enough time, I could get the eye open and my face began to look normal. I would lie back down and have the same difficulty each time I got up to use the restroom. These symptoms started lessening until they completely resolved between 7-8 am on 4/27/21. I have had similar symptoms with migraines (possible hemiplegic migraines) in the past, but I did not experience any headache with these symptoms. Now it is 11:44 am on 4/27/21 and the only symptom that remains is general malaise and mild myalgias. I thought about going to the emergency dept during the night due to the facial drooping, but ultimately decided to wait it out.
PRIOR_VAX: Had minor joint pain and chills with first COVID-19 vaccine (see above details), but nothing like I experienced with second dose

Intense vertigo, similar to what I experienced during my previous vestibular neuronitis events.  It's effectively inflammation pinching the vestibular nerve, which can only be helped by reducing the inflammation with steroids.  Treatment was prednisone for inflammation, zofran for nausea, meclizine for the vertigo symptoms, and zyrtec for reducing fluid build-up due to allergies.   Extreme symptoms lasted 4 days of absolutely no movement or even open eyes, then 2 weeks of limited ability to move, now able to function, but still feel slightly dizzy.  My doctors believe the vaccination contributed with general inflammation, which, combined with the allergies, triggered the event.

42-year-old female with previous history of chronic/refractory immune thrombocytopenic purpera (ITP).  She received the Moderna COVID-19 vaccination on 4/13/2021 and subsequently developed headache, photophobia, diplopia and blurry vision.  She had outpatient labs 4/14/2021 with a platelet count of 8000 and presented to the emergency room.  She was seen by hematology/oncology and was started on high-dose dexamethasone for 4 days, IVIG x2 doses with an excellent response.  Platelet count on discharge was above 200,000.  Due to the headache and visual disturbance MRI and MRV was obtained which showed no evidence of cavernous sinus thrombosis however there was a question of idiopathic intracranial hypertension and ophthalmology and neurology was consulted. She had a fundoscopic exam with no evidence of papilledema.  Her headache slightly improved with acetaminophen and hydrocodone.  The patient was cleared for discharge home by hematology/oncology and will follow up with them in 1 week.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Recipient received dose #2 vaccine today, and almost immediately had response with witnessed seizure-like activity, with posturing, tonic-clonic movement of his upper extremities, and eye movement with lateral nystagmus. Loss of consciousness was noted. Symptoms lasted approximately 15-30 seconds, and patient was placed in a reclined position. He regained consciousness quickly and became pale and diaphoretic. He was normally responsive and answered questions appropriately. Initial BP 74/32, HR 38, SpO2 98%. He drank some Gatorade and had improvement of symptoms gradually over 15-20 minutes. Repeat BP 100/58, HR 78. No past history of seizures. One prior syncopal event after pain response with sports injury. No prior difficulty with dose #1. After recovery, patient reported immediate pain with vaccine administration, then vision went blurry and he lost consciousness. Mother was driving the vehicle, and she witness symptoms as well as nursing staff in the vaccine pod. After recovery, options for further medical evaluation were discussed given complicated vasovagal response with seizure-like activity, mother called pediatrician to see if he could be seen, they recommended ER. Mother chose to drive by personal vehicle, rather than EMS transport. Symptoms were fully resolved and patient was transported to ER for further evaluation by personal vehicle.

Patient received the vaccine on 4/5/21.  On 4/8 a strong pain developed in her opposite arm and migrated to her chest.  She couldn't even pull up her pants when going to the bathroom.  On 4/11 she developed chest pain and struggled to breath until 4/13.  On 4/13 she developed a strong pain in her right thigh which subsided on 4/15.  On 4/17 she started with a rah on the back of her left thigh which continued to spread onto her torso, arms, legs, neck and chin.  On 4/18 she went to the ER and was given steroids.  She followed up with her family doctor on 4/19 and while at the MD office her throat, tongue and lips started to swell.  She was sent back to the ER on 4/19 and received more steroids.  She  went back to her family doctor after leaving the ER on 4/19 and completed blood work which came back on 4/20.  All the blood work (specifically allergen marker) indicated this was not an allergic reaction to any of her known allergies (as the ER MD assumed).  At that point, her family doctor recommended she visit an ER at another town to get additional help.  She went to the ER, on 4/20 and was given more steroids and told she had vasculitis.  The rash continued to spread all over her body.  The rash started as a blistery red and then shifted to red and purplish, black.  On 4/22 she saw her MD once again who diagnosed her with HSP.  She is certain this was a reaction to the covid vaccine, as she has only been to the md twice in the last two years; once for a pap smear and once for a flu shot.  She is a very healthy person with no illnesses until this vaccine.  Her skin is now peeling where the rash was.  She is also struggling with a severe mental fog.  She struggles to remember conv ersations.
ALLERGIES: slight allergy to red meat, dairy strong allergy to mouse epithelium

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received the treatment on April 8th around 4p. I came home with no thought of the vaccination. I abesent-mindedly tested my BP with an automatic cuff on the same arm around 6p. Around 8p my arm started to lose it's strength. In the middle of the night while sleeping, I woke up in pain. My arm felt like it had been broken with a significant amount of nerve damage. (It was a funny bone feeling from arm, elbow and wrist) It was throbbing and my feeling was numb from my shoulder to wrist. I started taking my husband's hydrocodone to sleep and continue daily function. Each day, my arm improved, however, I was no longer able to lift or move it with real intent. (It was like it was paralyzed)The weirdest things that my hand (fist) was never affected. I could use it as long as I did not have to move my arm or bend my elbow. The pain and lack of movement lasted 1.5 weeks. We I walked my arm appeared dead like a recent stroke victim. I went to the doctor the 17th of April( soonest appointment) . By then I was no longer taking pain pills but I did not have full range of motion. Now, April 27th, I can lift my arm up with no pain but my strength is still weak. At one point I thought the damage might be permanent, but every day the pain and the limitations seem to improve.
LAB_DATA: Dr. only did visual test. She told me to follow up if it does not get better.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I began breaking out with hives and bumps on my legs, arms, neck, scalp, and hands. It started three or four days after my second vaccine. The rash began on my legs and over the course of the next two and a half weeks, it spread to different areas. I finally went to an urgent care on April 15, 2021, to get a steroid shot because I was itching uncontrollably. They would not give me one and sent me to my regular doctor. She saw the rash and gave me a steroid shot, a prescription for steroids for seven days, and Hydrzyine for the itching.  I'm still having random bumps/breakouts here and there that consist of a couple of bumps at a time. I also felt as if there was a burning underneath my skin during this time. I'm currently rubbing Caladryl on the bumps when they itch. Most are gone,  but I did get two new ones a couple of days ago.

I received my vaccine Saturday the 24th. High Fever 104 degrees starting at 1:30am on April 25th lasting until 9:35 am. I took tylenol around 9 am so my fever went down to 102 degrees at approximately 9:35am on April 25th. Same day around 3:30pm my temp went back up to 103 degrees. That night was rough again with the fever staying steady at 103. Took tylenol again around 3 am and fell back asleep. At 5:40 am April 26th, (Monday) my temp was down to 102 degrees. Finally went down to 99.8 Monday April 26th in the afternoon. Around 8:10pm it went back up to 100.4 and about 30 minutes later it was back to 101. Held steady through the night around 101 degrees. It's now Tuesday but my temp is back down to 99 degrees. Sunday and Monday I had extreme body aches, sweating fits, unbearable headache, sore arm, shortness of breath, extreme fatigue, loss of appetite. It's now Tuesday April 27th and I still have the headache (not as bad), shortness of breath, and loss of appetite. I no longer have body aches and my arm is slowly feeling better where I had the injection.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On day 9 after my second  vaccination woke up feeling itchy, inflamed with severe joint pain in knuckles, hips, and feet and a hot scalp headache, extreme fatigue. On Saturday had the same pain/inflammation symptoms and began running a low grade fever (99.4-99.6) that was not responsive to ibuprofen. Ran a fever also on Sunday, 99.6, again not responsive to ibuprofen. Began taking Claritin in case this was a  serum sickness like reaction on Monday and that helped immensely, finally the ibuprofen was able to work and the fever went down. Today, Tuesday, I am still itchy all over, fatigued and with some pain but not as bad. I also took Claritin and ibuprofen on waking. While I have chronic health issues these reactions are totally new for me. I had four weeks of intense, relentless inflammation, headaches and extreme joint pain (my joints visibly red for weeks) (no fever after my first dose of the vaccine) but my doctors never mentioned SSLR. With the second dose I actually felt better for over a week, but then it all came back, was much worse and the delay was confusing. It was almost impossible to find information about delayed non-local reactions.  I am reporting it because other people need to know that SSLRs are possible with this vaccine and can be debilitating. Please let people know!
OTHER_MEDS: Low dose naltrexone 4.5 mg Lauricidin, 2 scoops daily multivitamin, 1 daily

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient with known alcoholism, found down and out covered in blood for an unknown period of time.  Brought to Healthcare Facility by ambulance for treatment, and planned to transfer.  Suspected GI bleed; when flight crew arrived, decided to intubate.  Failed first attempt, and patient when into cardiac arrest.  Was revived with CPR and 2 doses of epinephrine.  Pt also received TXA and 1 unit PRBC, and fluids.  Successful second attempt, though BPs remained labile.  Pt transferred to ICU and was notified that additional evaluation found bleed had actually occurred proximal GI tract (oral mucosal bleed, not esophageal).  Pt also diagnosed prior to transfer with multilobar pneumonitis, ascites secondary to alcohol cirrhosis, hematemesis/meme positive stool, leukocytosis and pancreatitis.  Was notified by ICU less than 24 hours later that pt was on vent and stable.

Day 1.  Evening, sore upper left arm. Day 2.  Cold and achy all day;  not chills, but rather cold from the core on out.  Stayed in bed bundled up with lots of covers, no sleep all day.  Got up every two hours to pee and eat something.  In a.m. could only navigate going downstairs by one step at a time with both feet and holding securely to rails on both sides, as I did not trust my knee, hip, ankle and feet joints and muscles.  By end of day could navigate stairs normally.  Fatigue, foggy mentally, and bicep pain and limited range of motion all day.  Night 2.  Woke at 3 a.m. with extreme headache; got up and went pee and drank a half cup of apple juice; headache gone in twenty minutes and went back to sleep. Day 3. Thigh and calf muscles of both legs, but mostly left thigh, spasm-ed with pain, off and on all day.  Body temp back to normal.  General achiness, fatigue,  lack of mental clarity, and pain itchiness redness of left bicep and limited range of motion continued. Day 4.  Nose bleed lasting about five minutes, mid-morning.  Achiness and fatigue not as severe; clarity returning. Days 5 through 7.  Gradual improvement of all symptoms. Days 8 through 14.  Final resolution of all symptoms;  able to confidently take dog for regular walk, and to do errands and important financial coversations.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 57-year-old female with history as detailed below presents to the emergency department for further evaluation of an allergic reaction.  She received her 1st dose of the Pfizer COVID vaccine at app 4:20 this afternoon. She states that approximately 15-20 minutes after receiving the vaccine she developed acute onset of hives and itching of her arms, neck and face.  She denies shortness of breath or chest tightness with the symptoms.  She was given 25 mg of Benadryl p.o. at the clinic prior to being brought into the ED.  Medication Orders Placed: diphenhydrAMINE (Benadryl) cap 25 mg (25 mg Oral Given 4/24/21 1918) Famotidine (Pepcid) tab 20 mg (20 mg Oral Given 4/24/21 1919) predniSONE (Deltasone) tab 60 mg (60 mg Oral Given 4/24/21 1918)  A history was obtained and a physical exam was completed upon the patient's arrival to the emergency department. History and exam were concerning for anaphylaxis versus allergic reaction. Initial vital signs as above are unremarkable the patient is hemodynamically stable.  Physical exam as above is benign no signs/ symptoms of anaphylaxis.     The patient's constellation of clinical and laboratory findings was most consistent with allergic reaction. The patient was re-evaluated after the above treatment/therapies and her condition/symptoms improved. Based on the patient's age, coexisting illnesses, labs, imaging, and exam findings, the decision to treat as an outpatient was made. I discussed my findings with the patient and she understand(s) and agree(s) with the treatment plan. All of the questions and concerns of the patient were addressed. The patient was comfortable with and in agreement with the established plan of care.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu Vaccine Novaris brand in 2012
ALLERGIES: bees, shellfish, flu vaccine, metformin, topiramate, penicillins

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 34 y/o female, with past medical history of Covid (1 year ago), who presents with dizziness and dry mouth onset post vaccination. Patient states that this is her first vaccination in the two-dose series. Patient denies previous reaction to vaccination in the past. Vaccination site to the L arm. NP and Paramedics at patient side. Patient provided with a bottle of water. All vitals within normal limits (122/71 BP, 99% RA, 73 HR, 10 Resp, Glucose 90). Patient placed in wheelchair and brought to lay on the Trendelenburg cot. At this time patient was placed on 3L O2 by nasal cannula. Patient at this time states that she is somewhat scared of needles and when she had Covid over a year ago, she suffered from dry mouth lasting 6 months. Patient states that the dry mouth she is experiencing now is the same after her infection. Patient states that a mint usually improves her symptoms. Patient denies sore throat, difficulty swallowing, difficulty breathing, itch or rash. Patient provided with a mint and continuously monitored by the NP and paramedics. Within 30 minutes patient symptoms improved, dizziness resolved, and dry mouth subsided with the use of the mint. Patient was able to ambulate to the bathroom with NP and female Paramedic at side. Patient states that she feels better. Patient was cleared to go home after being observed for 30 minutes.

On 4/10 I started feeling tired with muscle aches.  A few days later my skin started to hurt.  Clothing was uncomfortable when it moved across my skin. Those symptoms lasted about a week. Then as they started to lessen I had some back pain (Sciatic) and a sore throat.  Also the muscles behind my eyes were slightly painful and bright lights were uncomfortable.  Then about  4/21 most of the symptoms reduced and I was feeling close to normal.  Then on 4/22 I was brushing my teeth and noticed that I couldn?t spit water like normal.  I called my GP doc and she recommended I head to the ER.   After thinking about it I also remember on 4/21 while drinking something I had some water squirt out of my lips.  At the time I thought I was just being clumsy but in hindsight the muscle weakness in my face started on 4/20.   I checked into the ER on 4/22.  When I checked into the hospital my facial weakness was very difficult to notice.  By the evening of 4/22 it was noticeable if I tried to ?show my teeth? or make a big smile. By the morning of 4/23 it was very noticeable.  The morning of 4/24 I couldn?t move my lips, nose or eyebrows.  My tongue, jaw and throat were not impacted at all.   I was started on plasmapheresis on  4/24. I had another treatment on 4/25. I noticed facial weakness was very slightly recovering the evening of 4/25.  By 4/27 my facial weakness is still healing with noticeable improvement day to day.

68-year-old female presenting with shortness of breath and hoarse voice after her first Moderna COVID vaccination today. She took Benadryl at onset of symptoms and received additional by EMS. She now feels better but has persistent hoarse voice and shortness of breath although with unremarkable physical examination.   Given her history of similarly presenting anaphylactic reactions to foods, as well as symptomatic airway involvement, advised treatment with epinephrine for probable anaphylactic reaction.  Patient expressed agreement to this.  She received epinephrine as well as Solu-Medrol, with improvement in symptoms.  On reevaluation, she is breathing more comfortably and says that she feels almost entirely improved.  Repeat vital signs have remained stable.   Prescription for prednisone given for home.  Advised her to discuss symptoms and next steps with her primary doctor, although she probably should not receive her second vaccination.  She does have an EpiPen at home.  Strict emergency department return precautions for recurrent symptoms were reviewed and she expressed understanding and agreement.

Skin became severely dry and itchy. Rash and nonspecific skin eruption. Blanching erythematous papules and excoriation on arms and upper back.  No rash in groin. Well developed, well nourished, male in no acute distress, oriented and without outward signs of anxiety or depression. Complete examination of the scalp and hair, head, face, ears, nose, lips, eyelids and conjunctiva, neck, chest, breasts and axillae, back, abdomen, right and left arms, digits/nails,  right and left legs was normal except for the following significant findings: - Erythematous papules coalescing in areas into nummular plaques with scattered excoriations on the back, flanks, lower legs.  Eczematous dermatitis  - Start Triamcinolone acetonide 0.1% ointment BID over affected area, no more than 2 weeks per month.  - Reviewed side effects of prolonged steroid use including skin atrophy, telangiectasia, hypopigmentation, and striae. - Recommended bathing with lukewarm water, using minimal fragrance-free soap only in intertriginous areas. Options include Cetaphil and Dove.   - We discussed the importance of regular moisturizing (2-3x per day) with an emollient (Hydrolatum or Aquaphor) or thick cream (Cetaphil, CeraVe, Vanicream, Eucerin etc) even when eczema seems to be doing well.  - For itch and poor sleep, start hydroxyzine 25 mg PRN at bedtime. Reviewed potential SE including sedation.
LAB_DATA: Eczematous dermatitis  - Start Triamcinolone acetonide 0.1% ointment BID over affected area, no more than 2 weeks per month.  - Reviewed side effects of prolonged steroid use including skin atrophy, telangiectasia, hypopigmentation, and striae. - Recommended bathing with lukewarm water, using minimal fragrance-free soap only in intertriginous areas. At 2am 4/22 patient started to feel sick and sent a text that I didn't read until 630 as I was asleep.  She had severe muscle aches, hurt to move, hurt to breathe and felt like she was having a heart attack.  She felt like she might pass out and had some blurred vision.  At 630am, I  saw her texts and immediately brought her 2 tylenol and a large glass of water.  She went back to bed.  She woke up around 10:45 and was feeling decent except for a headache but no fever or anything so we went to try on some Prom dresses.  At the dress shop, she collapsed and had a seizure lasting around a minute.  She lost her bladder and was completely confused and incoherent.  She's never had a seizure before.  I scooped her up, brought her to the ER where they ran every test and scan imagineable.  Full blood work up and cultures, a chest xray, a CT scan of her brain and lungs.  Her temp was high 103-104 and she had full body chills and a pounding headache.  Her BP kept dropping and got as low as 81/36.  They threw 2 bags of IV fluids into her and admitted her to the hospital.  She had also developed a heart murmur.  Over the course of the night, her BP stabilized but her temp continued to spike and come back down with Tylenol/Ibuprofen.  She also had IV Tordahl for the headache.  Her inflammatory markers were high at 15.3 which we were told should be less than 1.  They reran labs in the morning but everything can back really low which they felt was a dilution effect from all the fluids so wanted us to follow up with her primary care on Monday.  On Saturday night, he lymph nodes were swollen to the size of ping pong balls but have since slowly reduced in size although still there.  Her labs were better from discharge and her white blood cell count was within range and her inflammatory marker was down to 1.7.   Her blood sugar was a little low.  She did pass out and have seizure like response to giving blood in the doctors office,  lost bladder control again, shot pupils, etc.  She is still stuttering over words, has some short term memory retention and has some motor function issues which they think is a result of the initial seizure and should resolve itself over time.  Her liver function tests were totally normal in the hospital but are a high now so they will be checking her out again next week.
LAB_DATA: 4/22: Chest Xray, CT Scan of Brain and Lungs,  4/22 & 4/23 & 4/26 Full CBC/Blood Cultures for drugs and infections/viruses, etc.  Clinic would have results from those labs.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Please note that I am the patient in question here, but also an physician, so I will write this in technical terms as best as I understand what happened.  For background, my cardiac history is important. I had a work-up for palpitations performed more than a year ago that revealed normal cardiac function (EF > 65% by NM myocardial perfusion study), normal coronary arteries, and significant exercise tolerance (I maxed out the treadmill test).  Usuallly I have to engage in vigorous exercise to raise my heart rate > 160 bpm. My resting heart rate is typically in the 50s or less.   On Jan 15, 2021 I had an elective cerebral angiography and embolization procedure performed. I was asymptomatic prior to this procedure.  The procedure requires general anesthesia for several hours.  I have had the procedure conducted a few months previously and it typically has an unremarkable recovery, one night required in the hospital.   After the procedure and following extubation, I had hypoxia on room air, tachycardia, wheezing and fatigue.  The working cause for this was suspected atelectasis due to general anesthesia and I was given bronchodilators.  While my breathing improved overnight, I was very tachycardic even while sleeping ? pulse greater than 130.  Overnight telemetry noted arrhythmias with sinus tachycardia.   The tachycardia persisted long after prior albuterol use so I had CTA chest on 1/16.  No PTE was noted, though some basilar atelectasis and mild upper lobe ground glass opacities.  I was discharged but due to continued mild hypoxia overnight, low grade fever (< 101F), and persistent tachycardia with any movement, I went to the ED on 1/17 for additional evaluation.   In the ED, I had tachycardia with arrhythmias noted (rate up to 160). Sinoatrial exit block noted on EKG and telemetry.  COVID-19 testing was negative by nasopharyngeal PCR and antigen testing.  Resting heart rate was > 90 even when sleeping.   Follow-up echocardiogram on 1/21/21 revealed depressed ejection fraction (40-45%).  Cardia MRI on 2/1 was performed to evaluate for cardiomyopathy.  Symptoms at this point were fatigue, dyspnea with even mild activity (e.g. walking), and tachycardia  > 140 bpm with even just walking.  My resting heart rate improved to 40s-50s.  It showed normal wall motion and ventricle size with slightly reduced ejection fraction. Cardiology recommended cardiac event monitoring which I wore for 28 days. It only revealed sinus tachycardia and bradycardia.   I still don?t feel great but able to do more physically than a couple of months ago.  I await further f/u cardiac imaging to see if there has been improvement in the heart function.
LAB_DATA: Summary of Testing:  1/16/21 ? CTA chest ? no PTE; bibasilar atelectasis, mild upper lobe ground-glass opacities. Troponin negative. 1/17/21 ? COVID-19 PCR and antigen negative, influenza A/B PCR negative, viral respiratory panel negative, BNP CHF ? normal, TSH normal 1/21/21 ? TTE ? EF 40-45% 2/1/21 ? Cardiac MRI with slightly depressed ejection fraction 2/1/21 ? COVID-19 IgG negative
PRIOR_VAX: Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine, dose 1 (listed above)

He had appointment for routine INR check which happened to fall 3 days after his vaccine, and INR was found to be 4.1.  There were no other identified explanations for the unusually high INR in him.  He did not have any symptoms of bleeding or thromboembolism.  He did have some arm pain so took a few doses of ibuprofen (which should not cause the increase in INR and he has been using ibuprofen prn the duration of his anticoag therapy)  He was asked to hold 2 doses and returned 1 week later, which was 10 days after vaccine.  At that time INR came down to 3.0 and CBC was ordered which came back normal for him.  He still did not have any symptoms of bleeding or thromboembolism.

Exactly two weeks after administration of the first dose - Friday, March 26 - developed tinging in both hands and all 10 fingers. Immediately ceased Cipro (prescribed in the ER for a prospective UTI) after only four days of a ten day regimen due to possibility it was a side effect. Received the second vaccine on schedule despite symptoms.  Condition progressed to include tinging in both feet, then both legs started "falling asleep."  Sensations are never the same from one day to the next - changing from tingling to pins and needles to numbness/falling asleep to twitching to compression. Cannot track a pattern as to which limbs fall asleep when and for how long (is it positional, food/drink related, is there a specific length of time, symmetrical, etc) but it's systemic, diffuse and bilateral. On the date of the filing of this report (April 27, 2021), I have experienced a 50-75% decrease in the intensity and frequency of the symptoms but they have not yet completely resolved. It is 6 1/2 weeks since my first dose, 3 1/2 weeks since my second.  No presence of any other neurological symptoms - no weakness, no loss of sensation (even with feeling of numbness), no loss of strength, no cognitive impairment, no falling, no blurry vision. No pain.  No indications of any nerve damage whatsoever, so it seems to be uncomfortable and annoying but not dangerous.  Saw a neurologist six days after onset of symptoms and he ran several tests (listed below). While I understand it is impossible to track whether this is definitively vaccine-related, especially with an adjacent emergency room visit, the timing seemed too coincidental to completely dismiss as a possibility. I have not had any neurological symptoms prior to this point in time, and they seem to be dissipating over time without any intervention. I file this report with the hopes that with this new vaccine, any information is helpful and if there is a chance this is a rare severe side effect, perhaps others have reported the same and risk factors can be tracked.
LAB_DATA: MRI of cervical spine - April 6 - NORMAL Bloodwork - April 8 - no sign of any previously unknown conditions EMG - April 26 - NORMAL - no sign of any nerve damage

Returned again the following day and admitted for 2 days. Pain management, antibiotics, Corticosteroids and testing followed along with administration of oxygen. Within minutes, patient stated she was very light headed and felt like she was going to vomit. Patient then proceeded to pass out, but returned responsive within 30 seconds. Patient came to, but was unable to speak or respond immediately. She was able to nod her head and open and close her mouth. However, she was not speaking. When prompted with the question of whether she felt like her throat was closing, she nodded her head. However, patient continued to breath effectively and swallow. I asked if her lips were tingly and she responded yes. I asked if they felt numb and she responded yes. I proceeded to give her 25mg of oral diphenhydramine. Patient swallowed the liquid with no trouble. She was slowly opening and closing her eyes. Within minutes, patient started to speak again as well. I continued to ask her what her name, date of birth, day of the week and patient was able to correctly answer. She continued to take very deep breaths, and paused in between speech. I asked the patient to count backwards, which she successfully did. She was also able to squeeze my hands, and felt pressure on her arms and legs. She complained of her legs and arms "feeling numb and tingly". She was also able to provide us with her cell phone code and told us how to reach her husband. EMS arrived within 10 minutes of initial reaction. She left the pharmacy and was transported to local hospital.

She developed headache a few minutes after Vaccine administration.  After her 15 minutes she left and went to her office. within 15 minutes after being in her office, she reported that she was having chest pain, swollen tongue, and not feeling well.  I checked her throat and she said she has had this kind of reaction in past and doctors have not found out the reason to her reactions.  She said she was told she is showing some symptoms of pre-development of Lupus.  She has not done Allergen's testing for food or environmental factors due to Insurance not paying for it.  Her blood pressure and pulse were taken a few times as follows and she was gradually getting better until 4:13 pm where she felt normal again.  She said her chest felt better, fogginess was almost gone, her throat felt normal, and her headache was less.   3:44 pm, Blood pressure:  157/97, Pulse 82. 3:47 pm, Blood pressure:  149/92, Pulse 78 4:00 pm, 150/104, Pulse 73  (she was talking to me while her blood pressure being taken) 4:05 pm, 149/96, Pulse 71; 4:13 pm:  150/95,  Pulse 72  She felt okay at the last vitals being taken and I asked her to call us again if her symptoms get worse.
HISTORY: Has started symptoms of Lupus in past 2 years.
ALLERGIES: Possible allergies to some environmental factors and some food.  Most are unknown as no detail Allergy screening has been conducted in past.  There are some known allergies to Bees' Sting and Tramadol.  She has had many allergy reactions in past but according to her, the real root cause has not been determined.

Hx of vasovagal syncope prior to vaccinatons. MD was called to evaluate a patient who had fallen. Ran to patient and found her laying on floor with staff members around her. MD was told she received her vaccination, then laid down on a bench and rolled off the bench when she passed out. bench was about 2 feet tall.  When MD assessed patient, she was laying on ground, awake, slightly pale, clammy with faint but palpable pulses on my exam. She was awake and alert. able to answer MD's questions but felt dizzy and had a headache. She was able to track finger, follow commands. She was lifted into a wheelchair and moved to a cot. vitals were obtained which showed BP 122/70, pulse 72, o2 sat 100%, RR 18. EMS was called after her fall given c/f head injury. We were instructed to not give patient anything by mouth. Paramedics arrived at 0805. assessed patient. Obtained vitals. positive orthostatic vital signs with HR jump >20, SBP drop ~20. Given patient could not reliably stand without c/f repeat fall, patient was taken by ambulance for further evaluation at hospital.
Syncope Episode during the monitoring stage following inoculation.

Shot received at 7pm on the 23rd (Fri). I felt a little giddy, likely due to the emotional impact of excitement for treatment (this happened to me with my first shot, and both times with my partner). Experienced what I felt was like feeling mentally a little 'out of it' a few hours in, maybe late that night 10-12pm. I did not have notable physical symptoms until exactly 12 hours after injection. Around 7-8AM I was woken up with body aches. I spent most of that day (Sat) taking ibuprofen and hydrating a lot. I had a small fever that peaked at 100.00 F after chills, etc, once this broke I mostly felt better. Sunday I had some minor aches. It is now Tuesday and here is the reason I am writing this report: I have had very low appetite since getting the shot, but I have pre-existing GI issues. This also happened on the first shot. Both times I have also had slight lymph swelling (mostly on first shot, and it was on the side of my body where injection was given, notably in the armpit, but possibly groin or shoulder). The only thing that has honestly caused me concern is my mental health: I have pre-existing psychiatric diagnoses and some extenuating circumstances (recent death in the family, needing to travel, job loss, pandemic, on top of major depression and PTSD) however I felt that my threshold for coping with day to day stuff has been blunted since getting the vaccine. It is manageable and I do think that it will go away as it did with the first shot. I felt like the last few days have been akin to "PMSing", ie; irritable, crying a lot. Contextually, there are reasons for me to be having emotional fluctuations, but I have therapy and have been off/on medications safely and usually have this fairly under control. The reason it was bothering me is I felt that if this happened to other people who had less support or managed diagnoses or other circumstances, it could be worse for them. My partner (who is BP2) has also felt a little more emotionally unstable than usual. We do not think this is from the psychological toll solely of vaccination, the pandemic, or reopening, as it seems to be unrelated to this. Sure, this is anecdotal, but I think it may be important, especially in the event of someone who could have psychotic or mood swing issues (ie: BP1 or schizophrenia, etc). Again, anecdotal, but on some online forums a lot of people have reported having similar mood instability when theirs was otherwise manageable (and these were people who were pro-vax, pro-science, etc). I am worried that if there is not a warning in the future, more people could pre-emptively have mental health adverse effects and not know why. I think it is very seriously from the vaccine. For me this mostly included appetite issues, insomnia (especially the night after I got the shot), crying more, irritability, feeling kind of "flat", etc. Perhaps this is just due to the body fighting and doing it's job. I felt however it would be irresponsible of me not to report it.  I have spoken with my mental health provider about this and do not find that I need further treatment but that I wanted them to know, and that I wanted to file a VAERS report additionally to help the study of the vaccine in case this happens to others.
OTHER_MEDS: Levocetirizine 5mg, Vit D (2000 iU) , Vit B12, Vit C
HISTORY: PTSD, major depression, general anxiety, essential tremor, IBS

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Given second dose of covid vaccine on friday in the right arm 04/23/2021. The day after the covid vaccine I ran a high fever from about 7:30am until about 9pm on Saturday 04/24/2021.  During Saturday I drank lots of water to combat the fever but I noticed blood in my urine.  The blood got worse through out Saturday into Sunday and I noticed slight pain in my lower back and lower abdomen.  On Sunday morning (04/25/2021) my urine was a dark burgundy color.  This was quite alarming as it was very thick and not as light as the day before.  I drank lots of water on sunday and made sure to watch my urine.  The urine stayed red in color.  I called a telehealth nurse  on Sunday and they suggested I go to Urgent care in the morning.  I woke up on Monday (04/06/2021) with less blood in my urine but still went to urgent care to be safe.  At Urgent care I received a Urine analysis.  The doctor told me there was blood and protein in my urine.  He ruled out a UTI or an STD. The doctor said there may be kidney damage since there is protein present but it cannot be confirmed with the levels. The doctor advised that I continue to drink liquid and watch for worsening signs.  The doctor said I should contact him immediately if the blood or pain gets worse. The doctor also stated I should fill out this VAERS form. Today (04/27/2021) there has been less blood in my urine but there is still some pain in my lower abdomen.  I will contact the doctor at the end of the week to let him know what has happened to my symptoms, he requested I keep him informed.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within a few hours of the vaccine, my menstruation began.  At first, it was a light spotting, then was a light-medium flow.  The symptoms also mimicked a cycle:  tightness in pelvis and very light cramping.  I am SUPER regular, so there is no doubt in my mind that this is related to the vaccine.  I keep track of ?my first period day? on paper each month.  Never have I had a intra-cycle period of light-medium flow.  Maybe a light spot upon ovulation.  But, just as quickly at it came, it left.  By the end of the day/next morning, it was gone.  It was like something passing through me:  in one moment, out the next.
ALLERGIES: Once had a contrast dye reaction in the hospital.  Subsequently, I elected to test for allergies overall and none were found.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient's mother called today and stated that he had a seizure this afternoon at 1:35 PM.  She stated that she and her husband are both nurses.  She happened to be off today and was home with her son.  She stated that the seizure was like a Grand Mal seizure that lasted approximately 5 minutes. She stated that he has had a diabetic seizure before when his blood glucose levels were low.  She stated his blood glucose was 71.  She said this was different, he had no residual after effects. He was not incontinent of bowel or bladder and he woke up quickly afterwards.  About an hour after the seizure he ate and only complained of a headache.  She gave him ibuprofen 600 mg and he put an ice pack on his head.  She said he is better. She stated that she is a nurse and this really scared her, since it was so different than any other seizure he has ever had.  She was thankful she was home.  She call his primary healthcare provider and she did  not feel he needed to be seen.

This spontaneous retrospective pregnancy case was reported by a health care professional (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of UMBILICAL CORD PROLAPSE (cord prolapse) and BLOOD PRESSURE INCREASED (elevated blood pressure) in a 29-year-old female patient (gravida 1) who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 037K2A and 032L20A) for COVID-19 immunization. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     Previously administered products included for an unreported indication: TDAP on 30-Nov-2020. Concurrent medical conditions included Pregnant, Lactose intolerance (mild lactose intolerance), ADHD (stable, changed from concerta ER methypenidate to Ritalin IR methylphenidate during 2nd trimester) since 2018 and Depression (since teens;stable,Wellbutrin discontinued with pregnancy). Concomitant products included METHYLPHENIDATE from 01-Jan-2018 to an unknown date for ADHD, PRENATAL VITAMINS [ASCORBIC ACID;BETACAROTENE;CALCIUM SULFATE;COLECALCIFEROL;CYANOCOBALAMIN;FERROUS FUMARATE;FOLIC ACID;NICOTINAMIDE;PYRIDOXINE HYDROCHLORIDE;RETINOL ACETATE;RIBOFLAVIN;THIAMINE MONONITRATE;TOCOPHERYL ACETATE;ZINC OXIDE] from 01-Jan-2019 to an unknown date for Nutritional support.   On 31-Dec-2020, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 27-Jan-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. The patient's last menstrual period was on 14-Feb-2020 and the estimated date of delivery was 18-Feb-2021. On 31-Dec-2020, the patient experienced EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY (Pregnant). On 27-Jan-2021, the patient experienced BLOOD PRESSURE INCREASED (elevated blood pressure) (seriousness criterion hospitalization). On 28-Jan-2021, the patient experienced FATIGUE (mild fatigues) and HEADACHE (Headache). On 29-Jan-2021, the patient experienced CHILLS (chills). On 30-Jan-2021, the patient experienced UMBILICAL CORD PROLAPSE (cord prolapse) (seriousness criterion hospitalization). The patient was hospitalized from 29-Jan-2021 to 01-Feb-2021 due to BLOOD PRESSURE INCREASED and UMBILICAL CORD PROLAPSE. The patient received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) beginning around the  forty-fifth week of the pregnancy. The cesarean delivery occurred on 30-Jan-2021, which was reported as Full-term. For neonate 1, with an APGAR score of 8 and 9 at (1, 5 minutes). The outcome was reported as Term Birth w/o Complications. Cord prolapsed hand presentation discovered at cervical check post-induction by balloon catheter. Immediate C-section delivery. Delivered at 6:10 am. On 31-Dec-2020, EXPOSURE DURING PREGNANCY (Pregnant) had resolved. On 29-Jan-2021, FATIGUE (mild fatigues) and HEADACHE (Headache) had resolved. On 30-Jan-2021, UMBILICAL CORD PROLAPSE (cord prolapse) had resolved. 04/01/2021 - Vaccinated at 3:00 pm . Waited 15 mins and then returned home. Around 3:30 pm I developed a metallic taste in my mouth. Around 3:35 pm I became very itchy with no rash or hives. Itching feeling felt like it was below the skin.  Approx 3:45 pm I called called Primary Care Physician and let them know what going on.  Around 4:05 pm my lips, tongue and mouth felt numb ( Novocaine like )   Around 4:15 pm  My Dr's office called me back and after describing my symptoms they told me to go to to the ER.  Immediately Went to Emergency Department.  Was seen by doctor and others. Skin had now began going back and forth from pale to red. Itching had increased .  Skin color began changing going from bright red to pale white and then back and forth. I was also now very light headed and very nauseous along with. I still had the metal taste in my mouth, was extremely itchy, and my lips and tongue were still numb.  Around 5:14 pm they gave me Pepsid, Vistaril, Deltasone.  We stayed there about another hours and I was released.  Was give a script for Deltasone that I had  filled that night.  I went home and went to bed.  04/02 - Woke up and had lost all sense of taste and smell. I was still itchy, tired, nauseous, lips and tongue we still numb. I called my Dr and they said they would see me on Monday 04/05. The symptoms continued all weekend and on Sunday 04/04 i developed a burning feeling in my lungs.  Monday 04/05 I went to see the Dr . The Dr prescribed hydrOXYzine . I did not do well on so it was changed to Zytec. Rested and tried to take it easy. Feeling in the lips and tongue came back.  No longer  nauseous .  I was still light headed from time to time. My lungs were still bunring and I was very short of breath. On 04/23 went to the doctor because I still am not better.  My lungs were still burning, I was  tired all of the time, I and  I was still light headed from time to time. They did blood work, EKG and a chest X ray.  On 04/24 I had a CTA because ( abnormal coagulation profile shortness of breath.  I was prescribed Albuterol in hopes it will be better.  I have a follow up on 05/10 unless things get worse. 04/27 This are not worse, but they are not really improved.  I am still tired all of the time. I still have shortness of breath,  my lungs are still burning, and I still get light headed from time to time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This adverse event took place after I received my first shot of Moderna on March 12, 2021.  Immediately upon injection, my tongue felt a tingling sensation for about a minute.  Then it began to feel numb.  My heart also started to beat very fast.  I focused on my breathing and tried to remain calm.  Thankfully, I had no itching, no swelling, and no difficulty breathing.  While my tongue remained numb for a few days, I also started to experience painful headaches, fatigue, chills.  No fevers - just a general feeling of hotness.  But temperature never raised above 99.9 via ear thermometer.    However, another odd thing happened. About one week after I received my first dose.  I decided to retouch my gray roots with a hair color I have used before  and never experienced any side effects.  However, this time, I had to the ER.  I died my hair at night, and the next morning I had  redness and itchiness all over my face and arms.  My face and tongue also became swollen and my throat tightened.  At the ER, I was put on prednisone and antihistamines and observed for two years.  I remained on medications for three weeks.

After providing the Moderna vaccine, patient passed out going forward in slow motion and head was resting on table, then immediately started seizure-like action putting him in an upright position and I put my arms out to keep him from going forward and then he opened his eyes and came to. After talking to him while in observation, he mentioned that it felt like he was out for 5 minutes even though it only lasted for about 10-15 seconds. He mentioned that 12 years ago this happened (someone had thrown a rock and it hit his hand and when the nurse went to clean it, he went cold and when he came to it was exactly how it was after getting the vaccine). He only recalls feeling cold. When patient was about to leave, I suggested to him to reach out to his PCP to see if it's ok to give his 2nd dose with us or if he should be observed in a clinic setting. I did a follow up call a few hours later and he is doing fine.

When I got out of bed the morning of 4/1/2021 at 8 am, I went to turn off my humidifier in my bedroom.  In turning off the humidifier, I leaned slightly to the left, felt the vertigo, and fell down on the bedroom floor.  I could not do anything to keep myself from falling. Though able to stand up and walk a few minutes later, the vertigo persisted for several days. I did not have another falling event; however, since then I have restricted my head movements to avoid re-triggering the vertigo. To this day, at times I feel at risk of re-triggering the vertigo when I move my head too quickly, though I have resumed my usual daily activities and exercise routine.

I received my second dose of Moderna on April 9, 2021.  Because of my health conditions, they observed me on-site for 30 minutes. I am very glad they did. Immediately upon my second shot, I experienced: -severe headache behind left eye; -swollen and numb tongue -numb throat -itchy and tight lips -felt winded after speaking simple sentences, but I could still breathe without obstruction.  For the next 5 days, I had fevers and chills, and felt fatigue, and felt the 'pine and needles' sensation throughout different parts of my body at random times. The scariest thing was that the right side of my face, including part of my tongue, went numb. I could still control my face though.  The numbness lasted two weeks.  14 days after I received my second, my skin all over my arms, legs, and face has become tight, dry, and extremely sensitive.  Many things seem to cause me to feel itchy or get a rash.      I feel like the covid vaccine has put my immune system in some sort of active high alert. I am doing or eating things as normal, but find I am now allergic to some things. For example, we put Tajin seasoning on our tropical fruits. I just touched the Tajin and ate some on one slice of watermelon. My hand, mouth, tongue, and throat became itchy. My throat felt a little tight too. I immediately stopped eating, washed my hands, and took benadryl. I was better within hours, and the next day I ate watermelon by itself.  On Day 17,  I decided to eat a Hannah sweet potato for lunch. My brother even made a yellow curry with them. Immediately - my lips, tongue, and throat became itchy. My tongue felt swollen. Again, I stopped, washed, and took benadryl. Later I played it safe and ate chicken with rice.  Since the second dose, I have noticed this pattern of having an immediate allergic reaction to things that normally didn't make me allergic.  I have informed my health care provider.  I am continuing to keep track of all my experiences.
CUR_ILL: Severe allergic reaction to hair dye. Resulted in trip and treatment at the ER.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My mother received the vaccine on 4/17/21.  The following day she was bedridden.  Her condition did not improve over the next two days.  My wife and I were out of town and I was maintaining phone contact with her every few hours to monitor how she was feeling.  She expected she would feel bad for a few days...  On 4/21/21 she appeared to feel better in the morning when we spoke and she advised me she was going shopping with a friend.  Around 2pm on 4/21/21 I received a phone call from her friend advising she was taking my mother to the emergency room at the local hospital.  My mother was unable to answer basic questions and we believed she was suffering from a stroke.  The following day when I arrived back in the area I spoke to the neurologist on call who confirmed my mother did have a minor stroke but that it was in an area of her brain that should not effect cognitive functioning.  My mother was given a CT scan, brain MRI, spinal tap and an echocardiogram.  All of these tests came back "normal".    My mother is still in the hospital and has shown no improvement.  She is agitated and confused.  She asks the same questions over and over again.  The neurologist has advised that they have no explanation as to why she is experiencing these symptoms.  The only thing that changed was her receiving the covid vaccine.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin B-12, chantix, blood pressure medicine and ant-acid

SYMPTOM_TEXT: * Tuesday, March 16th, I received my first Moderna shot. No immediate symptoms, felt fine. * Thursday, March 25th (9 days post-vaccination), I was sitting at my desk and experienced some kind of visual distortion (my computer monitor bounced up and down 4 times in quick succession, even though I was perfectly still). Got up from my desk and laid down, and it went away. * Tuesday, March 30th (two weeks post-vaccination), I started experiencing persistent dizziness/imbalance. It was manageable for the first couple of days, and I still went about my daily activities. * Thursday, April 1st, symptoms got noticeably worse. I had a really bad episode of vertigo/dizziness in the afternoon. This spell of bad symptoms lasted until Saturday evening/Sunday morning. I wasn?t falling down, but I would describe it as akin to being on a boat in rough seas or a plane flying through a storm. Pressure in head and ears was intense. I?ve had longstanding tinnitus, but pitch/volume definitely seemed to change somewhat. My neck was incredibly stiff, and my throat felt somewhat ?tight? (tonsils or lymph nodes in neck felt enlarged). Took ibuprofen and Benadryl on and off over next several days. * Tuesday, April 27th, symptoms are ongoing. Still having imbalance, dizziness, and non-spinning vertigo, though less severe than previously.

I received my second dose of the Modern vaccine about 3:15 pm on April 22. That night I went to bed experiencing the same symptoms as I had after my first dose of the vaccine: soreness in vaccine site, stiffness in my arm, headache, stiff neck, body aches and feeling lethargic.  At about 5:30 am, I was awaken with a strange, unexplainable heaviness in my muscles and chest, my breathing felt shallow and I had a strong urge for a bowel movement.  I got up, had a bowel movement (not diarrhea), began to sweat and shake, and then began to have the dry heaves, but did not expel any fluid, not even bile. At this point my husband said he heard strange sounds coming out of the bathroom and came to check on me.  He found me passed out and said I was making strange snoring sounds and thought I was having difficulty breathing.  The next thing I remember is him calling my name and struggling to gain consciousness.  At this point, I was very dizzy and nauseous and lay down on the floor.  My legs starting shaking sporadically and my breathing felt shallow.  When I felt stable enough, my husband helped me back to bed and I fell asleep immediately and slept for about an hour and half.  I was awakened by the same symptoms and proceeded to repeat the previous episode.  After I passed out for the second time, my husband insisted that I go to the emergency room.  In the emergency room, I underwent bloodwork, an EKG and they began administering IV fluids and 4 mg of Zoran.  All test results came back normal.   I was discharged and went home.  After being released, I did not have any further episodes.  The only symptoms I experienced after the episodes were a headache and backache, which were not relieved by Tylenol, lethargic and slept for the better part of the next two days.  I did not at any time during these episodes or after or prior to the vaccine experience a fever, sore throat, cough, vomiting or diarrhea. I am not at this time, nor have I for many years been on any medication.  In the past, I have been highly sensitive to medications and anesthesia and have experienced adverse reactions, even to some over-the-counter medications.
LAB_DATA: bloodwork , an EKG, 4 mg of Zofran and IV fluids All test results returned normal
OTHER_MEDS: multi vitamin, D-3, omega, C, calcium, glucosamine, CoQ10

Pt received the 1st COVID vaccine (Pfizer, Lot #: EW0179, and expiration date: 08/2021) at 11:02 AM. Patient flagged EMT  while sitting in the observation area. EMT  attended to patient who complained of "lightheadedness" and "shortness of breath." Patient was conscious, alert, and oriented to person, time, place, and situation (CAOx4). EMT explained to the patient that he wanted to have the patient move to the zero gravity chair, so vital signs and a full assessment could be done. Patient agreed and expressed that she felt steady enough to stand and walk on her own to the zero gravity chair. Patient then walked to the chair, while EMT  followed. At 11:27 AM, baseline vitals were taken, while patient was sitting: blood pressure: 118/88, heart rate: 72, respiratory rate: 12. Skin was warm, dry, and normal for ethnicity. Nurse then responded to EMT  with patient. Patient has a medial history of diabetes and is prescribed Metformin. Patient claimed she is allergic to Penicillin. Patient also explained to EMT that she was fasting so she had not had anything to eat or drink today. EMT offered the client a water, but she declined. EMT educated the client on the importance of eating and hydrating before a vaccine and recommended the patient do so before her next appointment. Patient continued to be conscious, alert, and oriented to person, time, place, and situation (CAOx4). A second set of vitals were taken at 11:33 AM, while patient was standing: blood pressure: 116/84, heart rate: 72, respiratory rate: 12. Skin was warm, dry, and normal for ethnicity. Patient tested negative for orthostatic pressures. EMT advised patient to stay an additional 30 minutes to continue to monitor for additional sign and symptoms, but patient refused. Patient then left the site with a steady gait, accompanied by her husband and daughter.

First noticed symptoms after waking up during the night roughly 14 hours after receiving the 2nd dose of the vaccine. Felt EXTREMELY fatigued and my heart was racing. Fell back asleep and woke up again around 8am. Symptoms persisted. Extremely tired and fatigued and heart was beating fast. Resting heart rate of around 100bpm which jumped to 120bpm when I moved at all (including just rolling over in bed). This persisted throughout the day, and I stayed in bed. In the early afternoon (about 24 hours after 2nd vaccine dose) I started to feel aches in neck and back and started a headache. Took my temperature and had a fever (101). Aches/headache continued to get worse throughout the afternoon. Finally around 4:30pm I found my Tylenol and took a dose. This substantially helped reduce all my symptoms; although I was still tired, it was much less than earlier in the day. Took a dose of Advil around 7:30pm and went to bed about an hour later. By morning, my symptoms were practically all gone, I was just slightly more tired than normal that day (2nd day after vaccine). I did not take any more medication.

The day after the second Pfizer shot, I felt worse and worse as the day progressed with the symptoms we were warned were possible:  feeling awful with no appetite; temperature 100.8 (normal for me is around 96.3); injection site red and hot.  They gradually eased up the third day with temperature down to 98.4. I felt wiped out for the next few days even after my temperature was completely back to normal.  However, I also experienced other symptoms.  Starting on the third day, I experienced headache, neckache, and a more painful lower back and left hip than I've felt in decades � to the point that I could barely walk.  I had been in a bicycle accident when I was 14, resulting in a concussion, a cracked lumber vertebra, and damage to my coccyx so severe that it was removed two years later.  I've had a weak left hip ever since.  However, since that accident, I've had regular chiropractic treatment, and, in the last 20 years, clinical massage treatments.  As a result, my spine has stayed healthy and I've led a normal, active life.  It was therefore a complete shock when those old symptoms returned after the Pfizer second shot.  Although they've improved with chiropractic and massage treatments, after 6 weeks I'm still not able to walk very far due to the pain.  Feeling quite depressed, I talked with my chiropractor yesterday and found out that some of his patients have also experienced the onset of long ago familiar symptoms at sites of old injuries.  He suggested that I file a report with the CDC in case these symptoms are not just coincidental.
HISTORY: See information included in the Adverse Event description

SYMPTOM_TEXT: By 6pm I noticed something wasn?t right. I could t get warm, even when sitting in the sunshine. By 9pm the chills had turned to fever. My temperature at 9pm was 101.2F.  I also had a headache and started to feel a bit shaky.  By 10pm I had body aches and was in bed with 3 blankets on me and still could not get warm. My temp was 102.7 at 10pm. I tried to sleep. At midnight I awoke to a fever of 104.8 and could only cry. The worst body aches, headache, racing heart and dizziness, nausea and vomiting (after additional aspirin were taken to relieve the fever). I was very weak in an alarmingly rapid period. I stayed in this condition until approximately 6:30am on 4/26. At 7am my temp was 102.5 and I found it hard to make it back and forth to the bathroom, due to dizziness and weakness. By noon, the temp was back up to 103.1 and I could barely cry, as I suspected I was then  close to dehydration. I focused on hydration and slept as much as possible. The fever slowly came down to its current 100.4 at 11pm on 4/27.  This has been an alarming reaction to a vaccine. I have had serum sickness previously, so maybe that is a factor that should also be considered. I hope this is helpful.

At approximately 12:45pm on 4/27/2021, patient received his first dose of Covid19 (Moderna) vaccine, given by Pharmacist on duty. During the 15 minute observation period following the vaccine, the patient's father asked the pharmacist to check his blood pressure.  While the pharmacist was checking his blood pressure (approximately 2-3 minutes following the vaccination), she notices the patient was starting to look pale and shut and squint his eyes as if he was having trouble focusing his vision.  The pharmacist questioned the patient to make sure he felt ok, and the patient said his vision was going black and he was  getting dizzy and lightheaded.  The pharmacist moved nearby objects out of the way to prepare to lay the patient on the ground. When returning to the patient, he was staring blankly, hunched over, unresponsive, no pulse felt on a 5 second check, and had rheum dripping from nose and eyes. At 12:50pm the pharmacist instructed technician to call 911. Patient was lowered to the floor in the supine position where he remained unresponsive and no pulse could be felt on a 10 second check, but chest rise could not be evaluated as patient started to have convulsions.  Convulsions ceased after approximately 15 seconds and patient started groaning and moving his head and said he could hear but he couldn't open his eyes yet. Patient remained supine and the Pharmacist continued to carry on conversation with patient until EMS arrived at 12:57pm to evaluate patient. EMS attributed  the instance to syncope related to the vaccine.  The patient denied ambulatory care to the hospital for any further evaluation. Patient denied history of fainting expect for ?one unprovoked episode at his grandmother's house when he thinks his blood sugar got too low.?

I ate food before I took 200 mg - an hour later my symptoms had progressed to include doubling over in pain and nausea at which I ate a little more food and took 400 mg more (total 600 mg). At 600 mgs my symptoms abated enough for me to eat a small breakfast (10 am). 4 hours later the nausea and severve doubling over with pain cramps returned which is when I ate more food at took another 600 mgs of ibruprofen.  I went to bed at 7pm that night (usual bed time is 9:30)  I used ibruprofen to manage my symptoms all that first day ? the next day I was exhausted from feeling so beat up the day before but thankfully no more cramping or nausea. I developed pulsatile tinnitus in my right ear about 24 hours after the shot. Didn't think it was a big deal at first but it came back every evening and even now my ear still feels weird all the time even when the whooshing goes away. For about three weeks it came back nearly every night now it just happens on random nights. I didn't get my second shot because I didn't want to risk making it worse.   I am very-much a vaccine advocate but I think it's strange that I never hear anything about tinnitus as a common symptom. When I went looking I immediately found a TON of anecdotal evidence of the Moderna vaccine causing tinnitus from people stories almost exactly like mine. More should be done to understand this.

At approximately 3am (~13 hours post-injection) I experienced chills. I was asleep in bed and was awakened by my own shivering. My bedroom was its typical temperature, I had my usual bedding on the bed, and my wife (next to me) did not feel that the temperature was unusually low. I added additional blankets and suffered through these chills for approximately one hour until they passed.  At approximately 9am (~19 hours post-injection) I began to experience severe body aches and fatigue. I got up, had breakfast, and then slept approximately 3 more hours. I awoke for lunch, played with my children, and then fell asleep for approximately 2 more hours. Body aches continued through the day. Over-the-counter Tylenol was sufficient to ease the discomfort. I would describe the level of body ache as similar to having completed an extremely strenuous physical activity the previous day; the last time I can remember feeling this sore was following a multi-day 100-mile backpack trip at high elevation. At present (10pm, approximately 32 hours post-injection) the body aches are subsiding but still present. My fatigue is also subsiding.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient reported that they were experiencing tightness in their arm and believed it swelled initially. They left the pharmacy area and went to get Tylenol that was recommended by the pharmacist. They then began to get lightheaded and had syncope, attempted to get back up and the cashier asked to if they wanted to sit, but fell again. It was not clear initially to the employee who was helping them they had received the vaccine. 911 was called and the employee helping them let the pharmacist know they had just gotten their vaccine. The immunizing pharmacist went to check on the patient. EMTs were already helping the patient and had taken his blood pressure which was normal the lightheadedness had stopped and both sitting and standing blood pressure was the same. He had an elevated heart rate per the patient but didn't know any of the numbers the EMTs had taken. His father was driving him. He was not experiencing any symptoms and the injection site had no swelling and was otherwise unremarkable.

with post-vaccine diarrhea/rotavirus infection;   Information has been received from the authors in a published literature article titled as stated above concerning to a child patient of unknown age and gender who was enrolled in a study to analyze the group A Rotavirus (RVA) genotype prevalence during consecutive RVA seasons (2014-2016). The patient's pertinent medical history, concurrent conditions, drug allergies/drug reactions and concomitant medications were not reported.       On an unknown date the patient was vaccinated with an unspecified dose (1-3) of rotavirus vaccine, live, oral, pentavalent (ROTATEQ), (dose, frequency, Lot # and expiration date not provided) oral for prophylaxis.         On an unspecified date in 2015 (season reported as 01-DEC-2014 through 30-NOV-2015), the patient experienced post-vaccine diarrhea (Rotavirus infection) and was hospitalized. A Rotaclone enzyme immunoassay was performed in 2015 by using stool sample or eluted fecal material from diaper which tested positive for Rotavirus of group A (RVA) and unspecified genotype.  The authors reported the importance of continuous RVA surveillance post-vaccine licensure to identify emergent RVA genotypes and other gastrointestinal pathogens causing Acute Gastroenteritis (AGE) and to guide treatment and intervention strategies.   At the time of the report, the outcome of rotavirus infection was unknown.    The reporting authors considered rotavirus infection to be related to Rotavirus Vaccine, Live, Oral, Pentavalent (ROTATEQ).     A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.  This is one of several cases from the same article (US-009507513-2104USA007698, US-009507513-2104USA007699).; Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-2104USA007698: US-009507513-2104USA007699:

The consumer reported he is on Eliquis for DVT behind his right knee that is still there; cataract surgery; neuropathy; He has gained five pounds; The first shot he took, his arm turned red; wanted to sleep a lot; weird dreams; He has been on the walker for 8 months now; Monoclonal gammopathy; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer, based on information received by Pfizer (manufacturer control number:COMPANY-BMS-2021-037416), license party for apixaban (ELIQUIS).  This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of NEUROPATHY PERIPHERAL (neuropathy), CATARACT (cataract surgery) and GAIT DISTURBANCE (He has been on the walker for 8 months now) in 80-year-old male patient who received apixaban (Eliquis) tablet (batch no. 1708750) for DVT. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below CO-SUSPECT PRODUCTS included Covid-19 Vaccine for an unknown indication. Product or product use issues identified: DRUG INEFFECTIVE (The consumer reported he is on Eliquis for DVT behind his right knee that is still there) (seriousness criterion medically significant). The patient's past medical history included Pre-diabetic, Proctectomy, Sinus operation, Appendectomy and Drug allergy (sulfa). In 2018, the patient started Eliquis (batch no. 1708750) (Oral), 5 milligram twice a day. On an unknown date, the patient started Covid-19 Vaccine (unknown route). In 2020, the patient experienced MONOCLONAL GAMMOPATHY. In August 2020, the patient experienced GAIT DISTURBANCE (seriousness criterion disability). On an unknown date, the patient experienced NEUROPATHY PERIPHERAL (seriousness criterion medically significant), CATARACT (seriousness criterion medically significant), WEIGHT INCREASED (He has gained five pounds), INJECTION SITE ERYTHEMA (The first shot he took, his arm turned red), SOMNOLENCE (wanted to sleep a lot) and ABNORMAL DREAMS (weird dreams). The patient was treated with Surgery (cataract surgery) for Cataract. The action taken with Eliquis(Oral) was unknown. At the time of the report, NEUROPATHY PERIPHERAL, CATARACT, GAIT DISTURBANCE, MONOCLONAL GAMMOPATHY, WEIGHT INCREASED, INJECTION SITE ERYTHEMA, SOMNOLENCE and ABNORMAL DREAMS outcome was unknown. The patient received apixaban at a strength of 5 mg. The consumer reported he was on apixaban, 5 mg twice daily by mouth for a DVT behind his right knee that was still there. He started the medication three years ago. He stated he had to get his glasses. He had cataract surgery three or four years ago. He has neuropathy and believed it was affecting his right eye. He has had the neuropathy for quite a while. He finally went to neurologist and figured out he has neuropathy. The neurologist did needles. The neurologist found he also has MGUS (Monoclonal gammopathy). He stated it was a protein that was formed in the bone marrow and goes into the blood stream. He stated he has had it for a while. It was over a year ago when he found he had it. He stated the neurologist gives the test to people over 70 years old. The neurologist said it was idiopathic or pre-diabetic that caused it. He has gained five pounds. He stated he has to get off the chocolate. He was walking every day. The patient uses a walker which he stated was driving him nuts. He has been on the walker for 8 months now (Aug-2020). He reported he had his COVID shot and would not go through it again. The first shot he took, his arm turned red and it bothered his thinking. He put something down and misplaced it. After the second shot, he felt really bad and wanted to sleep a lot. He did not feel like doing anything. That lasted for a day. It came back a week later. He stated he has been busy and working on taxes. He reported he had weird dreams right after having it. For Eliquis(Oral), the reporter considered NEUROPATHY PERIPHERAL to be not related. No further causality assessments were provided for CATARACT, GAIT DISTURBANCE, MONOCLONAL GAMMOPATHY, WEIGHT INCREASED, INJECTION SITE ERYTHEMA, SOMNOLENCE and ABNORMAL DREAMS.     Case Assessment Drug: ELIQUIS Injection site redness, Sleepiness, Abnormal dreams, Monoclonal gammopathy, Drug ineffective, Cataract, Weight gain,Walking difficulty Per Reporter= Not related Per Company =Related   Drug: ELIQUIS Neuropathy Per Reporter= Not Related Per Company = Not Related; Sender's Comments:Medical Evaluation Comment: This 80 -year-old patient had multiple events after receiving apixaban therapy. This patient also got vaccinated for COVID-19. Elderly age with medical history of pre-diabetes are likely the risk factors for the reported events peripheral neuropathy, cataract and gait disturbance; hence considered as not related to apixaban. Drug ineffective is inherent to the nature of pharmacotherapy and is considered not related to the suspect.
HISTORY: Medical History/Concurrent Conditions: Appendectomy; Cataract operation; Drug allergy (sulfa); Pre-diabetic; Proctectomy; Sinus operation

The vaccine was administered at a hospital. It was not administered at a military facility. Medical history included hip replacement four years ago in 2017 (First right then 2 months later left) and knee replacement six years ago in 2015 (both 2 months apart). There were no concomitant medications. The patient previously received the first dose of bnt162b2 (BNT162B2, Solution for injection, Lot Number: EN6203), administered in Left Arm on 25Feb2021 (at 76-years-old) for COVID-19 immunisation and experienced bad headaches. The patient received the second dose of vaccine on 17Mar2021. On 29Mar2021, she was not hurting and went to brunch with friends. Afterwards (on the same date, 29Mar2021), she was sitting and got the worst pain through her side that ran down her left leg and to her ankle. She drove herself home but was in such misery. She went to the emergency room the next day, on 30Mar2021, wherein she had a CT (computerized tomography) scan that showed a blood clot in her lower abdominal area. She was taking pain medication every 6 hours, or she could hardly stand it. On 08Apr2021, she went back to the emergency room because she could hardly stand it. She was kept in observation status but was not admitted. She was scheduled to have another CT scan on 06May2021. She is not sure what they will do because the nerves are wrapped around it. She also mentioned that her doctor wants to do a biopsy. The pain was also running down to her ankle. She stated that she has had both of her hips replaced in the past. She added that her doctor will do an MRI (magnetic resonance imaging). He will put in a drain if it has not shrunk. The doctor can't do anything because the nerves are all tangled up (2021). As corrective treatment, the patient was taking pain medication for the blood clot and pain through her side that ran down her left leg and to her ankle. Outcome of nerves are all tangled up was unknown, while outcome of the other events was not recovered.
